column14: Love these shoes. I've had the black suede style for over two years. I wear them constantly (and they still look great). Since mine were suede, I was sure to use the proper sprays/protection on them, or I'm almost certain they wouldn't have lasted as well as they have. I've paid double the price for other casual shoes, and considering how well these have lasted, I can say they are well worth every penny. I do get many compliments on these shoes (from both young and old). I'm looking to purchase a pair for my daughter now (she loved them as well). column6: Altra Women's Lone Peak 2 Trail-Running Shoe
column14: This may or may not be a super helpful review.  Despite by comment that the fit is as expected, it took me four attempts to get the right size. but I wanted this shoe because of the width - I have wide feet and most smaller sizes only come in medium widths.  I normally wear a size 6.  I tried this at a store and deemed the size 6 a good fit.  I ordered from Amazon for a better price.  The size 6 came and there was a good inch of space beyond my toe and it felt too loose.  I returned the 6 and ordered a 5.5.  This was now too tight with my toe jammed at the end.  I opened a chat with Amazon and someone helped me get another 6 and he waived the overnight shipping fee.  Next day, I had the 6, tried it on and it was tight!  Having not returned the 5.5 yet, I compared the two and they were exactly the same length.  Got on the phone with Amazon this time and was again helped with another order for a 6 with overnight shipping waived.  Lo and behold, the fourth pair, and third size 6 fit!!  Despite all that, I'm glad I persisted because the shoes are very comfortable, great for walking which is really all I do in a pair of athletic shoes.

column13: Good shoe for a wide foot.

This will be my initial review, received the shoes yesterday and did a quick 2 mile run.
Reviews said that the shoe ran small, and because I usually wear a 4E and the shoe is only available in 2E I got a 9 1/2. It fits good enough not to return but I think I should have gone with a 9. For my wide footed bretheren the 2E is spacious enough for those of us who typically wear a 4E and I would not pass over this shoe because of the lack of a 4E option.

The feel is great very cushiony, mind you I'm coming off of shoes that I went about 500 miles over the limit on. So, my opinion may be swayed.

The feel is great, lots of control being wide footed I don't feel like I'm hanging over the edges. Impacts feel consistent no matter how I land on the shoe which is something many complex running shoes lack.

column6: Skechers Performance Women's Go Walk 2 Super Sock 2 Slip-On Walking Shoe
column14:
These shoes carried me through three weeks of traveling. I wanted something stylish and lightweight to pack for an extended trip. These fit the bill perfectly. I used them as dress shoes under pants, which was not perfect, but they also did not stick out as much as wearing full sneakers would have. The ridged bottoms are not overly obtrusive and so it does not look as if you are walking around in sneakers, even for those of us with large feet (I'm a 8 to 9).
I also used them for day to day site seeing. They seemed to offer the same comfort as my athletic shoes in terms of extended walking around. They pack nicely and came back to their full shape easily even after being squished in an overly packed suitcase for almost 24 hours.
However, these can't substitute for athletic shoes if you want to engage in fitness walking or running. I tried both, and there is not enough support. I did not think there would be, but it was worth a try.
I liked these so much that I purchased two additional pairs on my trip in other colors.

column6: TOMS Men's Classic Rope Slip-On
column14:
My first first Toms, after all the skepticism on if they would be comfortable etc, I just decided to try it. Always liked the style, but wanted something a little different from the plain colours I see all the time. The stripes added a bit more.

Pros: First off, I was pleasantly surprised at how comfortable these were. I am not a shoe expert nor a professional with the biology of the human foot, all I can say is these are one of the most comfortable casual footwear I have had in some time. And this is the case when having to wear them a couple hours well. There was no irritation or uncomfortable feeling after wearing this all day even.

Secondly of course is the look or style. I did buy this one for the stripes and the variance to the regular plain colours. I must say I am going to buy them again in the different colours because they are true to the pic, but honestly look better when you actually receive them.

Cons: Not so much a con, but the one thing for me that was different from most other shoe brands is they come a little bit bigger. Not as in a shoe size or anything. It is probably why they a comfortable, but they fit great. It is just something to keep in mind for people who may have slim feet like I do, you can probably get away buying a half size smaller with these. That said, this is just a personal preference how I like my footwear snug, so by no means a design flaw or anything, hence I could not take off a star!

column13: I loved these shoes at first - they fit so nicely ...
column14: I loved these shoes at first - they fit so nicely I felt i could wear them forever. Though they were slightly more narrow than expected. I have flat feet though, and the arch support actually gave me a lot of foot pain when walking around without them on. Very infrequently do I find shoes where the arch support actually fits on the arch of my foot - it's always slightly off, too flat or too high and in the wrong places. Similarly, it made the bottom joint of my big toe on my sole pretty achy. Additionally, after a while of wearing them, I noticed both my big toes were going numb. Then, I noticed nerve pain and pinching on the outer side of my toe where the strap crosses over on the inside of the toe loop. It sucked! It was really painful and numb for about ~3 weeks after not wearing them anymore. I tried a couple of times to wear them again after it healed, but the toe strap just keeps getting WAY too tight way too fast and I can feel it constricting - it makes sense that my nerves were pinched. I haven't seen anyone else complain about this though, so I'm wondering if maybe the shoe was too small or something and hitting my foot in the wrong place? The size 7 were WAY too big and the 6 were bordering on too small. Sucks because they were so cute

column13: Best shoes on the market at a good price!
column14: I love DC Shoes.  Mostly because they are VERY well made with premium materials, last a long time (which may be bad for them), look great with many styles and colors, are the best value in the shoe market, and are COMFORTABLE!  These are wide with a big toe box with plenty of room which makes them very comfortable.  They're easy to put on and take off without untying them.  What can I say, i think they're the best shoes on the market.  This style, the Stag series, however, is not my favorite.  The Pure series seems to use thicker materials and be more substantial (heavier) and I just like them better than the Stag series.  But if you like a lighter shoe you may like these!  Be sure to shop around different websites, the Amazon sellers like to jack their prices all over the place.  I've found some DC Shoes on other sites that are $20 less than the Amazon sellers are selling them for.

column6: Buxton Mini Trifold Wallet Card Case
column14: I love it, but I'm not in love with it. The color is very pretty. It has adequate space for coins, cards, and money. Without anything in it it is kind of thick, and putting anything in it makes it definitely thick, but it's a manageable thickness (in the event you aren't wearing tight pants with tight pockets).  I really like that the coin pocket has an expandable side to allow for more change if needed and I really like that there is a snap to keep the wallet closed. As far as other cons, the card slots are pretty tight and hard to get cards in and out. However, since it's leather, I'm expecting it to loosen up over time as the leather gets worked with use, so it's not that bad. I prefer snaps over velcrow or zipper to keep the wallet shut, but it would have been nicer to have perhaps two snaps or a bigger snap with reinforcement to keep it more firmly closed on the sides.  And as a personal preference, I would have liked a grommet or eyelet in order to put a snap or lanyard on the wallet to hook it on my belt (for constant fear a wallet will jump out of my pocket and get lost or stolen). So I'm going to buy an eyelet and install one myself someday. Overall, I really enjoy the design and quality and look forward to using this wallet.

column6: ASICS Women's GT-1000 3 PR Running Shoe
column14:
I love these shoes. They are incredibly comfortable and gorgeous!
I have flat feet. Like no arch at all. My friend read that Asics GT-1000 4 are great for us archless people, so I went straight to Amazon. I wasn't crazy about any of the 4s, but I saw these 3s and fell in love. (Pink is my favorite color)
The shoes come with bright pink shoelaces, as well as bright pink ribbon shoelaces.
After the shoes arrived, I left town for 10 days and took only these sneakers. Without arch supports, which I have needed in every pair of shoes for as long as I can remember, these were incredibly comfortable. We spent an entire day walking around stores and tourist sites and my feet weren't achy when we got home.
I highly recommend these shoes, especially if you have arch problems.

column6: Danner Men’s Mountain Light II Hiking Boot
column13: These are the Best Boots Ever.
column14:
I'm 55 years old, and these are the best boots I have ever had, period.

I had s pair back in the '70s, and I never forgot the glove-like fit of my Mountain Light IIs then. Between college, getting married, career, building a house, and moving, I lost them. But I never forgot the fit and feel of my Danners. No other boot I have ever worn came close, and as an avid hiker, I've been through many pairs over the last 30 years.

Got my new Danners last Thursday! After just three days of light-duty wear to begin breaking them in, I can tell these are not one iota less in craftsmanship, fit, and feel than my originals! I waited way too long to get a replacement pair. Do yourself a favor: get some for yourself. You won't go wrong, in my humble opinion.

Teva Women's Original Sandal
column13: solution for small ankle strap here (just a bit of sewing)
column14: So I already have several Teva sandals and I knew my size was a 9. the strap on the ankle was a bit tight but I could get it attached alright.  I am 5 foot 7 inches and weigh 155 pounds.  I made a small modification to the location of the velcro and it added about a half an inch to the circumference of the strap.  You really only need about an inch of velco overlap to secure the shoe.  My solution was to shorten the furry part of the velcro down to an inch (actually remove the stitching and detach it from the strap and cut off part of it and sew / reattach it back the strap.  secondly, move the prickly velcro closer to the end of the strap.  that way the length of strap that wraps back on itself is less allowing the strap to be looser around your ankle.  Now (after the mod) these are the perfect sandal and the strap is loose enough I can slide if off over my heel without having to un-do it!  I can also make it a little tighter if I plan on a lot of walking.  I have to have arch support and am always putting arch inserts into all my shoes, however, i find i can wear these all day and have no problems.  The strap makes them much more secure (you may miss the slap, slap sound that regular flip flops make) they feel like flip flops, but are great for all day and walking.  they seem to squish my toes together less than the original kind with the over the toe strap too.  I am really happy with these now and am trying to restrain myself from buying more in different colors!  Hope this helps you all.

column6: Buxton RFID Wizard Wallet - Exclusive
column14: I really do love this wallet. I've been a fan of Buxton wallets for years as they're well organized and compartmentalized. But, in learning about preventing identity theft I was advised to get an RFID wallet. I was delighted Buxton had one similar to my pervious Buxton wallets, but it was smaller so I was very skeptical about whether I could fit my things into it, or if I'd even like it. Anyway, I've been using it for over a month now and it's awesome. It holds my currency, coins and dental picks on one side, my license and a little comb fit in the outside insert for easy use and display, and the credit card compartment holds all my cards as well as some important papers I folded to fit. It also takes up less space in my purse. It's great! I feel safe now when I'm on public transit and in other public places where I'm told people steal personal and financial information using radio frequencies. So, I highly recommend this item!

(I received comments on its first client visit.) The bag is beautifully made. I love the details, the lining, the handles, and that it sits flat to the floor without tipping. The interior pockets are oddly sized (narrow and deep), and there is not a dedicated business card or pen pocket, which was a disappointment. I decided I could live with that because the bag is so gorgeous, especially in the chili color that I selected. It's a keeper.

column6: Saucony Men's Type A6 Running Shoe
column13: Fantastic racing flats... but not as good as the Type A5
column14:
Owning the A5, which I love, I ordered the A6 and expected more or less the same experience. Unfortunately (at least for me), Saucony changed the slim bottom of the A-series with its signature little rubber triangles into a more generic Saucony EVA and rubber version.
The result is a shoe that feels more like a trainer (think light version of Kinvara) and less like that special pair just for racing day.
Saucony did manage to make the shoe even lighter, which is pretty impressive, but it has less ground feel and grip (could just be perception because of the thicker sole) than its previous iteration.
It is still a fantastic racing flat, just not as good as its predecessor in my opinion.

column6: Timberland PRO Men's Hyperion Waterproof XL ST Work Boot
column13: I have really wide feet and I hate steel toe
column14:
I have really wide feet and I hate steel toe. Years ago, I got a job that forces me to wear them...after a long search, I determined that Timberland steel/composite toe are the only boots I could adequately break in and wear comfortably. I've worn their Pro-Titans for years without an issue.

The ironic thing about these Hyperion boots is the huge ad campaign they had advertising, specifically, their comfort. I regretfully bought in. These are without a doubt the most uncomfortable boots on the planet. The toe box is waaaaaaay too small (size 12W for me)...I can't bear to wear these things for more than a few minutes. I have to wear them untied and loose laced just to make them somewhat bearable. They also weigh a metric ton.

I kept them figuring it would take a week or so to break them in. I've been wearing them for over a month now, with zero improvement. Can't return them, so they'll be dropped in a donation bin soon.

Haven't had any issues with them falling apart as others have said here, but that's probably because I can't tie them, so they don't flex much. I don't doubt that the mesh on them would come apart if they were worn properly.

Unless you like paying $160 + for twin paperweights, I'd avoid these. I notice those "when you're feet hurt...." commercials have finally stopped airing...I guess Timberland figured out how much these boots suck.

column13: Stylish AND Comfortable (and stable heeled) Shoes
column14:
I love stylish shoes but having spent the majority of my career wearing super supportive and comfy fitness shoes, it's always been hard to get my feet to not protest at wearing heels. Then, I broke the joint of my bones just beneath my toes on my right foot and it never healed properly, SOooooo finding stylish dress shoes (with heels) has REALLY become a challenge!

I tried a number of shoe lines on Amazon and every possible size and width of the Madden pumps (which look really smart and sexy) but could not find a single set that I could wear for more than a few minutes without pain.

THEN, I happened upon the Bella Vita Women's shoes and bought a darling pair of blue (faux Alligator pattern) heeled sling back sandals and with a simple gel shoe cushion in sole, found a fun and gorgeous pair of shoes that can be worn for dressy occasions or casual.

Next, I decided to try these Platform Pumps to wear with dresses and skirts - again, they can be worn with dressy outfit or fairly casual (slacks or nice casual skirt). I believe the sizes are pretty accurate but I've been buying a half size larger and, the wider "C" width so I can put the gel sole inserts in and not irritate that right toe area - which is very sensitive.

These are IMO one level up from the typical 'comfort shoe' lines yet they are truly comfortable and I love that they have a nice heel to add height but, the squared heel and special rubber cushion on bottom of shoes make me feel confident walking in them as they provide extra support and stability - whether walking on marble/tile floors or, on carpet. Also, no worries about an ankle turning due to narrow/slippery pin point heels.

I had almost thought I would never be able to wear stylish high-heeled shoes again until I happily came across the Women's Bella Vita line!

He wore these for the first time today for preschool. They came home wrecked, and he limped the whole way home from preschool. He has a large blister on the top of his foot where the shoes rubbed, and the design on the shoes is scraped. They look like shoes we have had for months, not one day. Very disappointed. column6: White Mountain Women's Icon
column14:
I like the shoes enough that they end up being my workhorse for most outfits. They go with everything, and the heel height is completely manageable; plus, the wedge is very stable, and even mildly springy, so they're easy to walk in. The shoe laces aren't waxed, so they stay knotted, which is a plus. The only downside is that they are a little narrow and a little small overall. I generally wear between 8.5 and 9 women's, and my feet are consistently average/medium width in pretty much every manufacturer's shoe. Although you can adjust the laces, it's obvious that the shoe runs narrow. Note: the problem is not the suede material that goes around and over the widest part of your foot----the problem is really that the footbed is too narrow. The suede stretches out a little, so it ends up not being much of an issue, but it's worth mentioning.
----------------------
Update May 2016: Downgraded to 3 stars.

Just wanted to come back with a few comments after 8 months of use----
---The suede stretches out a LOT. When I first got these shoes, they felt very narrow, and now, they are extremely loose.
---Because of the stretch factor, the toe box becomes easily deformed. So instead of a rounded toebox, you end up seeing some of the lumps and outlines of your foot.
---At the base of the tongue, where it meets the rest of the shoe, the seams have started to rip. There's some white stitching under there, so its kind of noticeable.
---Surprisingly, the heel has held up perfectly well. There's almost no wear and tear, and that's usually the first thing to go on my shoes.

Overall, I think this was an okay shoe that I enjoyed wearing for a few months. But 8 months later, they are almost unwearable. Seems like a short lifespan, which is why I'm downgrading my initial 4 star review to 3 stars.

The rubber nose pieces and the rubber on the ear pieces are extremely comfortable and make it so he can wear these sunglasses all day long if need be. The polarized lenses are the perfect shade of darkness, they keep the sun out, but they don't hinder your eyesight at all.
The black plastic rims give a sporty look that any man looks to achieve with their sunglasses!
The carrying pouch is great because it helps keep the lenses scratch free and I'm hopeful these will help him keep them around longer than other pairs. He can never own too many so I'm extremely glad I ordered these for him!
Disclosure: I purchased this product at a discounted rate for an honest review.

Fit/size: Adequate length for what I am used to in a 10.5 D, though on the narrow side. In terms of reference points, I'd say it's similar in width to a Puma 10.5, but longer -- close to the Nike running shoes that I've owned. Nothing uncomfortable with arch support on a mildly flat foot.

Durability TBD.

For the time being, I am very satisfied for the sub-$30 price point.

column6: Vionic Women's Relax Slipper
column14:
I have plantar fasciitis and Achilles tendonitis and got these slippers to wear around the house. I have mixed feelings about them.

What I like: the contour of the foot bed and arch support are great. The furry material is nice and soft against the skin and the slippers feel well-constructed.

What I don't like: I wish the heel was just a little higher. I feel like my heel sits really low and my Achilles tendon feels stretched out when wearing them (i.e. hurts). The style is also very old lady looking and I don't like the Velcro closure. There's something funky about it and sometimes I feel the Velcro touching my skin and have to undo and redo the closure.

I normally wear a 9.5 - 10 women's shoe and I ordered the 9, which fits just right, so these run a little large.

column13: A size 7 is more like an 8 1/5 or a 9 and it says ...
column14:
A size 7 is more like an 8 1/5 or a 9 and it says MED and it's more like a double "E" width. Made in China. Too bad. Being soft..this is true but I have an American foot. And I do wear an American Medium width. There is also too much space between the top of my foot and the top of the shoe arch...the only way to keep it on is with the strap...but it's like wearing the box shoes come in... It says women's...this is more like a man's shoe.
The smallest size they offer is a 6 MEDIUM....which means it's more like a size 8 double "E" width. Should have had a market study in America and learned something about OUR shoe sizes that are most popular. Then they would have sold like crazy because they are like walking on a marshmallow....just can't keep them on or keep them from flopping all over your feet. Not safe and stairs would be a real safety hazard!

column6: Justin Original Work Boots Men's Stampede Boot
column13: I like the cowboy style because I've been very uncomfortable in ...
column14: I'm a woman and I usually wear size 11 women's boots. I'm required to wear steel toe for work. Its been difficult (near impossible in fact) to find a woman's boot in my size. These are lighter weight than other steel toe boots I've worn which makes them much easier to wear all day. I like the cowboy style because I've been very uncomfortable in other boots because a boot shaped for a man's ankle just doesn't work for a woman. Besides, cowboy boots are at least sort of unisex, I don't feel like I'm wearing clunky men's boots anymore. The thick rubber sole seems to provide enough cushion. The floors at my work are all concrete and I'm here 9 hours a day 5 days a week. I spend a lot of my day at a desk but the floors are still concrete. I've only been wearing these for a week but they are already better than my last pair of CAT steel toe boots that I paid the same amount of money for. My next pair of boots I will look for a shorter shaft, this one is fine, it hits right below the fullest part of my calf, any higher and they wouldn't fit and I would have had to return them. They are a good value for what you get, in my opinion. I wish the shaft on these was leather too because the synthetic gets a lot hotter in the summer but so far its been okay (think July). The main part over my foot is leather and they have a nice insole that helps wick moisture away from the foot. The stitching pattern is nice even though mostly its covered by my jeans. I'm hopeful that they will hold up over time. They are a little tight across the top of the arch, I have quite high arches but I think as they break in that will get better.

column6: Tourmaster SOLUTION WATERPROOF 2.0 BOOTS MAN
column13: Soles Tore Apart After The First Ride and Materials Are Cheap.  These Are Much Lower Quality Than The Originals.
column14:
Soles started falling apart after FIRST ride. One boot felt like it was an entire size larger.

Rider Type: Primarily long distance endurance and adventure riding.
Bike: BMW R1200GS Adventure
Age: 54
Years Riding: 30+
Size Boot: U.S. Men 9

I have a pair of Tourmaster Solution 1.0 boots that have traveled the world with me without a problem. After many tens of thousands of miles, it was time to retire them. I replaced them with Tourmaster Solution 2.0 boots and boy, what a mistake.

First the boots arrived and looked to be okay but made of much cheaper materials and with much less support than the originals. They are just not the as well made as the originals in materials or in quality. After trying them on, the left boot felt fine but the right boot felt an entire size too large. I bought some aftermarket foot beds and heel support and they then felt minimally okay but still not what they should. The heel cup is not formed well, the foot form is wide and they are just flimsy in terms of construction. Overall, they are just not made of quality materials and so the more they're worn the looser and less supportive they become.

I wore them around my office and my home for bit to break them in and last week finally had a chance to use them on some longer 500 mile rides. After the first ride, I looked at the soles and the rubber had actually torn in the middle of the boot. Incredibly, the rubber on the sole seems to be just a covering of some type and the foot pegs actually tore through the rubber making holes in the center of the sole after just the FIRST ride of about 500 miles. The sole also began losing chunks of rubber on the ball of the foot.

I have posted pictures below. One picture is of the sole of the left boot of the original Tourmaster Solution 1.0 after about 100,000 miles and 5 years of wear on several different bikes but with at least 30,000 miles on my BMW R1200GS Adventure.The second is the Tourmaster Solution 2.0 after one 500 mile ride on my BMW R1200GS Adventure.

These boots are not like the originals and should be considered to be even minimally adequate for any type of serious motorcycling.

column13: Your little girl will love them!

How adorable are these toddler rain boots?! I love the color and the pattern and your little girl will too. A lot of times you can have trouble getting kids to dress for the weather because the clothes are boring. Your girl will be begging you to let her wear these rain boots! Even though they don't have zippers, they are still fairly easy to get off and on. Your girl may even be able to do it herself since they just slip on. They provide great protection from the rain and puddles. My niece put them on just so she could jump around in the rain. She jumped around in comfort and style for quite a while and her feet stayed dry. And once they are worn, if they happen to get muddy or dirty, they are extremely easy to wipe clean. The material of the boots is durable and strong. They will really last and will probably outlast your girl's wear of them. I really love these boots and highly recommend them.

column13: If you're looking at them, GET THEM!
column14:
I must preface this by saying that I have NEVER written a review on shoes, but THESE shoes are so amazing that I had to! I NEVER wear heels, partially because I am 5'9", but moreso because I am all about comfort, and i've had very painful experiences trying to wear most heels. Seriously, comfort is of paramount importance to me, and I refuse to wear things just because it's cute.

I am happy to say that I didn't have to sacrifice comfort for a cute pair of heels, I finally found a pair that has both qualities. I honestly never though i'd find a pair of heels, wedge or not, that would be comfortable enough to wear all day. I was able to wear these shoes for a full day of walking around at work, and into the night without ever once being uncomfortable. I highly recommend these, especially for women who prefer comfort over cuteness...now you don't have to choose!

column6: Natural Uniforms - Women's Lightweight Comfortable Nurse/Nursing Clogs
column14: These shoes are as horrible as the bad reviews claim they are, and I should have listened to their wisdom. The upper is a thin, flimsy material like the thin craft foam you'd buy at Michael's or Joann's, and both shoes were bent/creased around the foot opening from either poor storage or rough shipping (they were sent in a baggie-type envelope rather than box); this made them completely unsightly. I'm a size 7 1/2 but typically need to order up with nice leather clogs - so I made the mistake of ordering an 8; these, however, were HUGE, overly wide, and floppy...I probably could have fit in a 6 easily. Perhaps these are men's shoes and I should have ordered two sizes down? Who knows. To top it all off, they're very "squishy" when you walk. I'm sure someone thought it'd be a good idea to make them like this for "comfort" or something, but what it does instead is a) not give any arch support, and b) make it completely unstable as you walk. column6: Dr. Scholl's Women's Paige Dress Sandal
column13: Superior comfort in a trendy heel
column14:
First of all, something not mentioned in the description of the product: the heel is 3".

I had my doubts when I was deciding whether or not to buy these. Typically, I've found mule-style heels to be rather narrow, and for my toes to end up crammed in the smaller hole. However, I was in the market for some nice summer sandals that could be dressed up or down, and I figured $40 and free returns would make them worthwhile to at least try out. Although normally I am a size 8, since I have never tried on Dr. Scholl's shoes and a size indication for a pair of Dr. Scholl's flats on Anthropologie's website showed that a 39 would start at an 8 1/2 for this company, I decided to go for the 8 1/2.

The fit is very comfortable from the first wear. I tried them on for an 8 hour shift where I would be constantly getting up and down, plus a movie date afterwards, and I found that my toes were only uncomfortable at around the 10 hour mark--way more impressive than I had expected, especially since I don't handle heels above 2 1/2 inches very well. The memory foam really does its job in cushioning your feet, and the heel is thick enough to allow for superior balance throughout the day, even when you're flagging at the end. :) I'm wearing them right now and I've found that the fabric has stretched to better fit my feet, and even though I've been doing some physical labor this morning in these heels my feet are still going strong without a twinge.

I bought the taupe version of this sandal, and I have to say that it really fits the summer season and dresses up my casual summer outfits without my putting any extra effort beyond a simple necklace. My one problem is that it does show dirt on the fabric, but that's to be expect for such a light color. All in all, this is a great purchase for the value and I may go for the black version soon!

column13: These shoes are good for all activies and look great for a simple look!
column14:
I am extremely picky about the type of tennis shoes/sneakers I wear. Every year I would buy the same style of white slide on Skechers for nearly 10 years before I decide to try a new style. I like a basic simple white shoe without laces and these were perfect! It's been three years, I am on my third pair, and I still adore them! They are comfortable to wear all day! The shoe has no laces to come undone, which is nice when I am hiking, biking, or at the gym.

There is always that fear about getting white shoes and how fast they dirty up, when these would get that way, I would throw them in the washer with some bleach and let them air dry. They lasted through several washings and lots of everyday wear and tear. The older pairs I have I retired to lawn shoes and they are still going!

I wore these with everything and liked the simple look that they provided. Most of all they didn't hurt my feet to wear all day, they have a nice tight fit, but not to tight, can be worn with or without socks. I liked these shoes so much I got a pair for my best friend last Christmas. These shoes are hard to go wrong with.

column13: Beautiful Vogs, but a little complicated
column14:
These are much daintier than most Fluevogs I have owned. They have a smooth leather sole and are built very narrowly.

Many people size up with Fluevogs, but I stick to my size 7 (I have one size 7 foot and one 6.5 foot) in most cases. My width is average. This pair, however, fit about one-half to a full size small, due to the pitch of the heel and the narrow toe box. In 7.5s my smaller right foot is happiest. I had a blister on my toe on the left side after the first wear. I regretted the purchase after trying to wear them a couple times at work. But I have to say after a few weeks, they are breaking in. I don't think they'll ever be for long walks, but they may just get comfortable yet. I'd give three and a half stars at this point.

If you go for them, I recommend a ball-of-foot pad to keep the toes from scrunching at the front. I also recommend sizing up. You may find the heel a little roomy, but the tie will keep your foot in them. I also replaced the ribbon with a silk shoelace, as it should have been in the first place at this price point.

column6: Ariat Women's Probaby Western Cowboy Boot
column13: Ariat Impresses with WIDE sizes! Yay!
column14:
Confession: this is my own first pair of cowboy boots... and I think I'm in love! I put them on to let the dog out. I put them on to run to the store. I put them on at home... "because my feet are cold!".

I've wanted a sort of all-purpose cowboy boot for ages, but I have wide feet! Not only are "C" width shoes rare, but many of cowboy boots have toe boxes which are purposefully pointy. Even if they were wide cut they would likely still painfully pinch my toes. When I saw this boot with it's cute, snubby little rounded-square (squoval?) toe box and then saw it came in a wide width I pitched it right in my shopping cart!

Fit:
Width: Depending on the cut I wear a "C" width shoe most of the time, though I can sometimes get away with a wide cut "B". These boots fit great in the toe box. I am so pleased! There is enough wiggle room that I can wear thick socks, too! :-)

Support: I have wide feet-- and high arches! It's kind of unfair. Anyway, these boots have a decent arch support in the shoe bed. You can reach in the boot and feel the arch support bump with your finger. Also, the boot is slightly snug at the instep. This provides additional support. Depending on where your feet are wide this might be uncomfortable for you, but keep in mind that this is leather and will stretch with time and wear.

Heel: My heels are not wide. This boot slips at the heel for me. Though I have read that this is normal in a cowboy boot, it feels like I wish I could get JUST the heel in a smaller size, since the toe-box and instep fit perfectly, but the heel feels big. I may get an insert for this. But as it stands this is fine with socks, as the construction of the heel on this boot is engineered to be a smooth bump inward that doesn't rub. I've worn the boots with shorty athletic socks and thick boot socks - though there is a bit of slip to the heel when walking, there is no painful rubbing for me whatsoever!

Boot Shaft: I've worn a friend's Fat Baby's out to help feed the horses before. They had a wider and shorter shaft than these Pro Baby boots do. That said, I have thin ankles and medium thick calves. These boots look better on my legs when I wear them with some boot socks. This also prevents the shaft from rubbing at the curve at the bottom of my calves when wearing them out for long periods.

Personal reference for fit: As a person with a normally 7.5 wide foot with high arches, thin ankles and medium-ish calves - I am quite comfortable in the 7.5 C boot. Though I would consider trying 1/2 size smaller if I could have tried this on in the store, the tiny bit of extra room lets me wear a thick pair of socks which is a good thing for boots!

Quality:
-The boots are well packaged- carefully filled with paper and a boot shaft form. They are carefully wrapped in a pretty tissue-like paper, too. (This means nothing without a good product, but it is a nice appointment which I could appreciate.)
-The leather is quite nice. It has a slightly oiled finish to it. Others mentioned that "Driftwood Brown" was distressed leather, but I see no distressing marks on my boots save where they now have walking-stretching marks from normal use. So far, the leather seems of good quality. With care (I am a regular saddle-soaper kind of girl!) they should really last.
-All of the stitching, from the piecing, to the shoe bed, to the decorative, down to what I can see inside the boot screams quality. This boot was well put together.
-The interior footbed liner and the sole seem thoughtfully engineered for comfort - both touches nodding towards form and function are present here.
-The styling is cute and thoughtful (stars - adorable stars! - and pretty lavender lining on a smooth brown boot), but functional (with wearable heel, sole and comfortable toe-box!).

Bottom line: I am really impressed with Ariat! I am gratefulto them for making not only a quality shoe, but for offering wide sizes. If you have wide feet you know how rare this is with many shoe companies. If Ariat continues providing quality wide boots like these I will buy again in a heartbeat! :-)

Side Note: I added some pictures of my boots (taken after a couple wearings) for your reference as to how they look on a person! You may notice my cat decided to check them out and say "Hi!", too. She is such a ham! :-)to them for making not only a quality shoe, but for offering wide sizes. If you have wide feet you know how rare this is with many shoe companies. If Ariat continues providing quality wide boots like these I will buy again in a heartbeat! :-)

column6: Columbia Men's Conspiracy Vapor Trail Shoe
column13: The shoes are amazingly light and are awesome for trail hikes
column14:
I bought 2 pairs of these (NOT from Amazon), but from Nordstrom's online sale. Could not resist the price at $29 per pair, but I am not giving them a 4 star because of the price. The shoes are amazingly light and are awesome for trail hikes. I wore them to Istanbul 2 weeks ago and they are comfortable all day. I had bought these for trail hikes since the Nike's I was wearing were not offering me enough traction on dirt trails. I was concerned about falls.

They only challenge I would issue the designers is the amount of cushion at the sole of the shoe which is rather thin (non-existent by most hiking shoe standards) and provide NO arch support. For that reason alone, I would not recommend running in these shoes because your knee and joints will be taking the pounding not this shoe. I have tried it and have come away with with shin and foot pain.

I am giving them a 3 star since they meet my original need to have very light weight shoes for hiking. And I like their style.

column6: Vasque Men's St. Elias Gore-Tex Backpacking Boot
column14:
This is an initial review. I bought these boots at the Rei store because I've always had issue with shoe sizes. I wear a 10.5-12 depending on the shoe. My feet are weird I guess. So I wanted to make sure the boot fit. I went with the 11.5 and the two sock method. Which ended up a little tighter in the toe than I would have liked. I'll be switching to the sock and liner method.

About the boot. I was struggling between this and the Vasque breeze, which is a much lighter and less rigid boot. But I ended on this one for a couple of reasons.

1. I had hurt my instep just prior to buying the boots and I felt much more support and less irritation in this boot.

2. It is an all leather boot which should last longer and prove more durable in the end.

Ultimately both felt great, I just preferred this one.

This boot is extremely rigid. Talking with the sales clerk, he said it takes time to break in this boot. However, after wearing the boot on a day hiking trip the next day the boot felt the way a new boot should and I had no issues with my injury.

I was a little scared about the breathability since it's a leather boot and I have eczema on my feet. But after the day, I found that my feet felt great and not irritated.

Like I said this is only my initial review. I will update this as time goes on.

column13: Will withstand rain but not comfortable.
column14:
I like the company a lot. I have other pairs that have lasted for years. He's in particular though feel tighter than usual, and there is no breathing room so you will be very sweaty wearing these. They seem well made to protect against any rain (hence the lack of oxygen/breathing feel.) It also has cushioning inside the shoe so that you won't feel every step you take as well as top cushioning which would help in colder weather. The elastic piece makes the shoe a little bit tighter than expected but this is a rain boot. It is also on the heavier side but that doesn't bother me for weather boots but good to know for travel.
The biggest flaw with this design is that the back of the ankle was design with ridges which I am uncertain as to why and he's not question well enough so that you feel every step take pushing against the back of your ankle which will likely cause blisters when wearing for long periods at a time. Unfortunately, these will most likely feel uncomfortable anytime you wear it and I will probably have to return these for the lower ankle cut.

column6: Unisex Polarized Retro Aviator Sunglasses - Nickel Plated Metal Frame Samba Shades
column14:
Ever since I can remember, I have always wanted to own a pair of aviator sunglasses. I think it's because they're popular in movies and TV shows. Everyone always looks so cool and suave wearing them, I just wanted to look famous! I chose to purchase them in the smoke color, because I was unsure of the green. I kind of wish I had ordered the green because the smoke is darker than what I'm used to. I wear contacts though so this might have something to do with it.
I would like to think I have an average sized head and these glasses fit me perfectly. The nose pieces make them really comfortable to wear for long periods of time and the lenses themselves aren't so big that they take over my entire face.
The quality is good, they're metal, not plastic so they can take a little more abuse such as being in my purse or console. They also come in an awesome carrying bag which I love because it helps keep the lenses clear and not scratched.
Disclosure: I purchased this product at a discounted rate for an honest review.

column14:
I have had a very frustrating time finding station boots for work (firefighter/paramedic). I've always worn men's boots (5.11, bates, etc), but they always slipped A LOT in the heel, were super uncomfortable after a few hours, and really hot (Texas). These boots are awesome! I can wear them all day and forget all about them! These are like wearing tennis shoes all day. And best of all, my heels don't slip anymore!

My only complaint is that they don't have a zipper on them (a very necessary item for my work). However, I found a solution for that! Get a pair of [[ASIN:B007DLVLDY LOCK LACES (Black)]] (See picture). I can easily take these boots on and off almost faster than I ever could with zippers. (Also note, in the picture I have them laced a bit different and not as high up for comfort.)

I normally wear a women's 10 or a men's 8 and have a somewhat wide foot, so I ordered a 10 in these and they're a smidge on the big side. With my next pair of boots, I will probably order a 9.5. It's been several months and I'm still very thrilled with my purchase!

column13: Wonderful Sunglasses with full protection from the sun!  You will not regret purchasing these.
column14: I purchased the Catania Occhiali® Sunglasses because I really liked the style and design.  I especially liked how the earpiece was designed I thought it gave the sunglasses a look of class.  I was really delighted when I received them so quickly on the 07/31/15, just two days after I ordered them.  I was very happy with the sturdy construction of the frames.  They are made out of a heavy material, not some flimsy stuff, but they feel light and comfortable on your face.  The hinges are stiff, so they stay form fitted to your head, but not so tightly that they are uncomfortable.  I was able to play a game of Badminton with them on and never had they fallen off once; and we played a hard game and won.  I took several hits to the face with the ball and the sunglasses never scuffed nor scratched.  I went 4-wheeling in them and they stayed on, no problem, even when we got off course and ended up going under low hanging brush, the sunglasses still hung on my face in the same place.  I might add I was not driving.  I chose to review this product for the UberZon Club, and let me tell you this is a great pair of sunglasses at a bargain price. The Catania Occhiali® Sunglasses are made to last.  They are comfortable, fashionable, and they provide 100% UVA and UVB Ray protection.  Now I call that a great pair of sunglasses! If you care about your eyes you’ll get a pair of these sunglasses for yourself and your love ones.  They work great!

column14: Being an insulin dependant diabetic with peripheral neuropathy(nerve disease) I have to have strong and comfortable shoes.This is probably my 4th or 5th pair of these and they've all worn well and lasted a long time.I haven't had any blister's etc while using Dr. Comfort's.They offer many styles in men and woman's and my podiatrist as well as a Nurses uniform store in town are retailers for Dr. Comfort.I would recommend them to any diabetic patient (as long as their Doctor approved).My insurance cover's one pair a year.Being behind a year I bought these for a back-up pair.Dr. R.,my podiatrist said was impressed with Amazon's price.If you need a dependable,comfortable shoe I recommend these whether you are diabetic or not.They may be more costly than some brands of casual/sport shoes but,they are strong and provide good protection.You can buy a cheaper shoe and have to replace them more often or get these and keep on truckin long after the others would  have worn bottoms.My opinion...5AUG15

column14: They are a little more narrow than a regular shoe, this is due in part to the fleece lining; so if you have wide feet, this may not be the one for you. My feet will sweat after a while, but I expected that as my last pair of slippers was lined with lambs wool and they did the same thing. I'm hot natured, but my feet stay cold, so I don't mind this; plus you can wash the liners, which is a definite plus!  I normally wear a mens 12 in boots, and a 13 in sneakers; so I went with the 13's and I'm glad I did.  The 12's would have been way to small.  So, If you are on the border line of going up a size, definitely order the larger one.  My house is also off the ground, so boots etc., make a lot of noise when walking, these however, are Very quiet! (This is Great since I have an infant). I like that there are only 2 holes on the top instead of the usual top full of holes, as I can walk through the yard and not worry about getting my feet wet.  Hope this review helps!

column6: Bamboo Dreamer-36 Dress Wedge
column13: Shoes acquired, now ISO a taller date.
column14:
ME: 5'2", 105 lbs, short but extra wide feet - on average I wear a size 6.5 but typically with grown-up shoes I have to settle for a 7 in order to get the width I need (unless offered in wide width).
REASON PURCHASED: Wedding Party shoe color contest

YAYS
1. SO comfortable - around the house only thus far
2. Accommodating for wide feet!
3. Color is even better in person!
4. Material is extremely soft
5. The price - seriously, I wish I had more weddings on my calendar!

NAYS
1. Ankle looseness - I do wish they gave me stability in the ankle area but for this price and the amount of wear they'll likely get, fo'get about it.

I think last time I wore heels they were almost always called "pumps" and the word "wedge" was slang for an uncomfortable underwear situation.
Okay ... maybe it wasn't *that* long ago, but even at my 5'2" stature I am unquestionably a flats girl at heart. Exceptions, of course, must be made, particularly when the word Bridesmaid is in play. I can't believe I even considered these shoes at such a height but I was so obsessed with the Lime Green that I glazed over the wobble warnings. The moment I opened the box my heart fluttered and while I was semi-mortified by the ever present elevation of my new lovely-lime ladies, I was motivated to make it work. I can't get over how comfortable they are and although I know comfort has a shelf life, I'll be in flops by then anyway :)

Seriously, don't let the low price throw you ... these are the real deal!

Thirdly, these boots DO NO LAST. I bought these because it's hard to find thigh high boots that aren't ungodly expensive. Apparently these boots are so cheap because they are cheaply made. I wore these boots ONCE and the right boot started to separate from the platform.

The one good thing I can say is that amazon promptly refunded my money and accepted a return.

column13: Good all around bike or light hiking shoe
column14:
As described in many reviews these shoes run small. I wear a size 9 1/2 in a regular shoe and 10 to 10 1/2 for running shoes. I bought these in a 10 and they fit fine with my thinner running socks but are too tight with thicker socks. The shoes are also narrow which is great for my narrow feet. If you have wide feet they will not work for you.

For function, I used them during a bike trip where we averaged 35 miles per day on hybrid bikes with flat pedals. The shoes were comfortable and transferred energy efficiently to the pedals. They are also useful for light hiking with reasonably sticky soles.

The shoes are good looking. I chose a color combination that I liked and happened to be steeply discounted. I would definitely buy again.

column6: Timberland Men's Chocorua Trail Gore-Tex Mid Hiking Boot
column13: Quality gives off great first impression.
column14:
I'm not qualified to review these boots from the perspective of a knowledgeable hiker; I purchased these in the hopes of getting my first pair of reasonable boots to begin the transition from day hikes to real hikes, and boy have they excelled so far.

In Florida, there isn't much rocky/steep terrain to test these against, but they've definitely proven they can keep grip in the wet stuff. Which is good, because you run into a lot of wet stuff around here. The waterproofing has so far proven true to the advertising. I haven't treated these with mink oil (yet) but for the one hike they've been out on, they've kept my socks dry even in two inch deep water.

Lately I've been breaking them in by wearing them during a normal day and they have succeeded in giving me confidence that I can wear them for a full 14 hours without feeling worn out or getting sore, tired feet. With high arches, I do experience a bit of fatigue late in the day, but it's mitigated by the lacing options of the boots.

The lacing eyelets seem to follow what I would expect to see on a hiep terrain king boot. I've no other previous boots to base my experience on but the hot button issue with these seems to be the quick lacing eyelets for the ankle and the quality of them. So far, I've approached them cautiously, but even with a good tightening they seem to hold sturdy.

column6: PF Flyers Unisex Bob Cousy Sneaker,Black,Men's 9.5 M US/Women's 11 M US
column14:
As a small child, I had a pair of PF Flyers, and loved them. I thought I was SO cool for having the same shoes as Benny "The Jet" Rodriguez.

Then I became a teenager, and wanted to wear Vans—to fit in—and I did, for many, many years. And I LOVED them. For ten years of my life, I wore Vans Prison Issues—with additional insoles. Then, THEN... Then those jerks at Vans discontinued MY shoe—and I had to choose a new one.

I re-stumbled upon PF Flyers—and read up on them—not just their history as a Sandlot icon—but how they build their insoles. Around this same time, I was living with an orthopedic massage therapist, and having knee problems. She mentioned that wearing insoles for so many years probably trained my feet/ankles/knees to not be able to support themselves properly (because the insole was doing it instead of my own body), and that I should wean myself off of insoles.

So I ordered a pair of PF Flyers, and decided to wean myself off of Doctor Scholes.

My life is so much better now. I have FAR less ankle/knee pain—and I can wear these shoes all day long. And I still feel cool wearing PF Flyers.

column6: Salomon Women's Fellraiser W Trail Running Shoe
column13: Awesome Hiking Shoes - no breaking in needed!
column14: Just came back from 10 days in Park City, Utah. I ordered the Salomon Fellraiser, Solomon XR Mission, and the Merrell Moab's to try. I have a small, narrow foot with a high arch and found the Fellraiser to be the most comfortable. I took them on my trip without wearing them first, which typically would be a terrible decision.... but these shoes are fantastic! We hiked up and down the mountains in Utah for 9 days in a row and these shoes never hurt my feet. I did put in my own insoles to add to the arch support, but there was no rubbing, blistering, etc. For a brand new hiking shoe, with no breaking in, these were even better than I could have imagined. They fit like regular running shoes and I was able to wear them with my regular athletic socks. Because of the mesh, they do get really dirty and the dirt comes right through to the sock. Overall these shoes were perfect for what I needed! Comfortable, good non-slip soles, and rugged!

column6: mel Dreamed by melissa Women's Mel Pop IX Ballet Flat
column13: Great shoes-order your exact Melissa size-not larger!
column14:
They are great shoes to own. They smell like berries and do cater to my "ooh look, shiny shoes" appeal. I own a few Melissa shoes but none of them were with a closed curved toe so my review is on what to expect when buying melissa slipper flats.

These shoes are the same sizing as other Melissa shoes (such as Melissa/Vivienne Westwood lines) so whatever size you are in that line, you will be with this. I am a true size 6.5 and I wear a Melissa size 6 so if you are a size 6.5 in regular shoes-order the 6.

Since these shoes are curved and narrow at the toe, you may feel a bit uncomfortable at first and think you will need a larger size (which is what I did at first) but DO NOT get a larger size because of your toes. Stick with what you would normally wear and when you wear them, they will begin to feel more comfortable.

So if you are a size 6.5, order the 6. DO NOT step up.
I ordered a size 6 and exchanged it for a 7 because I was concerned about the toe area, thinking that it would give enough room for my toes and they were too large so now I am exchanging and ordering back to a size 6.

The thing with these shoes is that tight is better as they bend and mold to your foot.

I hope this helps with anyone who wants to order a pair. Definitely worth having!

column13: love this bag but it seems other black bags are different, not sure why...
column14:
Before posting my review please not that my purse is the same one as pictured. I noticed other purses have buckle straps with pink lining and even black trim going around the lining. I also see the buckle straps ones have an outside keychain, mine does not. Since they are showing verified purchase, they received the item the same way I did, however, mine was supplied to me by the vendor in exchange for an honest review. I don't know why the black purses have different linings, colors, handles, key chains. Perhaps the vendor can address this issue.

I get nervous ordering purses off of Amazon since they are usually shipped folded up. I have had a lot of purses ruined due to this. I was happy this was synthetic since the material would probably handle a fold over. The day this purse was delivered, it was jammed in my mailbox, folded in half. I feared it would never take shape but it immediately did.

I like that it has a protective purse case over it. This is great for storing when not in use. I accidentally moved with some purses all in a plastic container and they all got stuck together where the material and colors came off. After that, I learned to make sure each one has a protective bag over it.

I do not see it notated so wanted to mention the bag has gold tone hardware. It looks really nice against the material and I someone who prefers silver tone hardware. It makes it look classy. Also, in the inner liner in the picture almost looks black. In person it is very clearly a chocolate/mocha color. I will be posting pictures to show you.

The first think I loved was there is a key link where you can easily find your keys by clipping them on a strap. This is perfect for someone like me. I have the biggest keys around so I don't lose them. However, I still seem to lose them in my purse. I can be searching forever trying to find them even though they are huge. This will eliminate that and save a lot of time. It will save time digging through my purse in a parking lot or in public which is a safety issues so that is my favorite part. I love the outer pocket; it comes in handy for a shopping list if you have the inside part all zipped up. I can be lazy and keep the bag unzipped, it stays closed though, and there is more than enough room for all of my stuff. People who know me know I carry everything but the kitchen sink. I don't know if it is because I like to be prepared or if it is because I am a mom. If someone needs something, I usually have it in my bag.

The inner pockets are perfect for my lip gloss, gum, phone, and anything I might need nearby and handy. The inside of the bag is very roomy which comes in handy with all my stuff. After you fill the bag, you could even place a scarf at the top or drape it over and it does not get bulky.

I am very impressed with this bag. The only think I would change is the material of the lining. I am used to something a bit softer and this seems almost paper like and I fear I might tear/rip the lining, which I have not done so in the past but fear it might happen with this bag. Since it has not ripped, I can't say it is an issue.or in public which is a safety issues so that is my favorite part. The only think I would change is the material of the lining. I am used to something a bit softer and this seems almost paper like and I fear I might tear/rip the lining, which I have not done so in the past but fear it might happen with this bag. Since it has not ripped, I can't say it is an issue.

column6: ASICS Men's GEL Venture 5 Running Shoe
column14: Never tried Asics before since I was a tried and true believer that my usual brand was the best. The best until recent years when each new pair I bought did not feel exactly right in the foot bed. I have wide feet and have to wear a wide width (4E), so those out there can surmise what the brand is without me directly saying so. Not sure if I can here! I was increasingly put off by the quality of this brand and their lack of correct fit and decided it was time to see what else is out there for wide widths since my feet ached more and more wearing them, no matter what model I tried.  I came across this shoe and I will never look back. I wear them everyday to the gym and walking and running on the treadmill for an hour is a total pleasure. Walking around on pavement for shopping and running chores, these behave just the same, very comfortable with great arch support and cushioning. I've worn these everyday for a good 2 months now and look forward to wearing them for many more.  I'm a new fan of Asics thanks to these shoes and look forward to staying with this brand for good.

column13: Extremely comfortable, easy on/off, fantastic travel shoe.
column14:
This is my second pair of these shoes. The first pair, I was provided poor fitment information from another website, so I ordered a size bigger than needed (I would have only gone a half-size bigger, but it's tough to find a 12.5). I didn't return them because I only paid like, $35 for them and I wore them for about a year. When those started to wear out, i was ready to re-buy them but at the correct size. I would have preferred a color besides black/black, but they still look good, and are pretty subdued in the looks department.

Super comfortable, soft, cushioned sole and insole. Not really designed for running, they're a phenomenal travel shoe. Easy on/off thanks to the Salomon closure system, and exceptionally comfortable for long days spent schlepping around a foreign city. I feel like I could wear these shoes for 16 hours straight.

Sadly, it doesn't appear that Salomon are releasing an updated version of it, but that's life. Get em while you can.

column13: I have avoided crocs because they are big clown shoes in appearance and I didn't want look like a.
column14: These are my first crocs.  I have avoided crocs because they are big clown shoes in appearance and I didn't want look like a ...you know.  I finally bought a pair because I am now swimming regularly and needed shoes that could get wet at the pool.  I hate flip flops, which abrade the tender area between big toe and second toe.  Well, I bought the crocs and they are awesome!  Very comfortable.  I have arthritis in my feet and the crocs are surprisingly supportive.  I wear them for long drives.  They are great at the dog park or in the back yard where I am likely to step in something that is very difficult to clean off sneakers but comes off easily with a hose or a wipe from my clogs.  Best of all, I look cool in them, and I know this because the younger generation is impressed.  Not the 20 somethings, who tend to roll their eyes, or my contemporaries who look askance and ask if I have been gardening but the stylesetters of tomorrow.  I wore them to the beach and a toddler and a four year old both patted my shoes. Now I want crocs in every color of the rainbow.

column6: Women's Classic Polarized Fashion Sunglasses - Liz Taylor \Untamed Lady\""
column14:
I absolutely love these glasses!!! I will only ever buy polarized glasses for so many reasons. The pair that I have had for about 15 years now, need replacing, I did not want to give them up, but there are a couple of spots on the lenses that are right in my view. So, when I was given the chance to review these at a discounted rate, in exchange for my honest review, I decided to go ahead and give them a try. I am rather very picky with certain things and sunglasses are one of those things. My eyes are extremely sensitive to light and I need to make sure that I have a high quality of lens to help reduce that sensitivity. With that said, these live up to my pickiness. The frames and lens combined are extremely lightweight and feel perfect on my face. They are quite stylish and seem very durable. Very happy to have these and be able to use them any time I am in the sun.

As far as the polarized lens goes, they are amazing! As I mentioned, I have owned a pair for 15 years. I have used them during winter, spring, summer and fall. I have worn them to reduce glare from the snow, the sun, glares off of cars or buildings. Even glare from the road, water or anything that will shine into your eyes unexpectedly. Honestly, you have to own a pair of polarized lens glasses. These are so stylish and gorgeous! They even come in a great protective box, wrapped in their own drawstring bag. This seller/company has gone all out to make sure that you are happy with their product, even including a nice Thank You note in the box.

column6: Dr. Scholl's Men's Harrington Work Shoe
column13: Great shoes, but no toe support
column14:
Overall I am very happy with these shoes. I work 9 hour days (almost all of it on my feet) and I don't have as much feet pain as I previously did. I still have pain at the end of the day, but it has been a noticeable improvement from my previous shoes/boots.

I've had them for about 4 months now (and worn them every day) and they have been very rugged. I haven't noticed the soul detaching, insole separating or holes/tears forming. Unless water goes over the top of my ankle, they appear to be waterproof.

That being said, my one complaint is that there is no significant support where my toes are. I work with dogs and after one dog (about 70 pounds) stepped on the toe of these shoes there has been an indention ever since. I've tried pushing it back out, but as soon as any little bit of weight is reapplied, the indention reforms. So, while I do like these shoes a lot and they have been a major improvement for me - if your job runs a risk of something heavy dropping on your feet, you definitely need something with more support.

column6: Chippewa Men's 6\ Waterproof Comp Toe 55161 Lace Up Boot"
column13: I want to get like gel insoles cause they aren't the softest to be ...
column14:
I bought these for my fiance who works outdoors doing all sorts of crazy things in every weather condition imaginable. I asked him about how he likes the boots, and he says "I bought a size 8 so they would be wide enough for my feet. If I had bought a size 7.5 (his actual shoe size), they would have been too narrow." So if you usually prefer a wider shoe, you may want to consider going a half-size up.

He also says: "I wear them all day. I want to get like gel insoles cause they aren't the softest to be just standing on. I've worn them 10-14 hours and only start hurting near the end but that's just fatigue." So there you have it. You can wear them all day, they aren't as comfortable as tennis shoes but that's how boots are, so if you have sensitive feet or know you have had issues before, you may want an insole of some kind. Having said that, he wears them for very long periods and has no issues with his feet (no bunions, no blisters, nothing like that).

They aren't made specifically for arch support, and he says "These don't really have a huge arch support. Just enough for me to know I have it there but nothing that really sticks out if you have high arches." So there you go.

Having said that, he got very sad when the shoes started to scuff because he said they look so nice. ;) That's what happens when you work! But yes, he loves them. I also have composite toe boots and I will say, I have dropped 200lbs of sand directly on my toe and had nothing happen (I didn't even feel it). They are a must-have for people who work around heavy stuff that might fall on their toes.

The frames are very durable and the parts of it that are chromed don't look like they were chrome plated, they look like the real deal. (You know how somethings are plated with metal and they just scream: tacky, halloween accessory, 99 cents, etc.? these don't look like that).

column6: Superfeet GREEN Full Length Insole
column14:
Having been told by a podiatrist that the only relief for my foot pain would be to purchase custom fit orthotics from him at a starting cost of $600, and not covered by insurance, I decided to look online for less expensive option. Hello Superfeet!

While I ordered the correct size, I found that the arch of the insole is farther forward than my actual arch is. In order to have my arch meet the arch of the insole I would have to wear them with my foot at least a half inch forward of the heel cup. Either way, the insole is uncomfortable for me. I asked another family member to try them on, we wear about the same size shoe, and they had the same issue. I opted to return the insoles.

Having said that, they do seem to be very well constructed, I found the width to be perfect for me (I wear a N width), and with the current return policy, I am considering ordering another style.

Update: Based on my experience with the return, I will not be ordering another pair.

column6: Merrell Men's Moab Ventilator Hiking Shoe
column14:
I used to think that shoes were just made to wear out quickly until I got a pedometer. I learned that I walk between 23,000 and 27,000 steps per week day at work which for my stride as a 6'2" adult male is about 15 miles per day Saturdays are usually around 20,000 steps or 13 miles.

I have worn these shoes almost everyday except for Sunday for the past 7 months. I figure a low estimate for the mileage on these shoes is about 1300-1800 miles. I weigh 195 lbs so realize that I'm not exactly stepping lightly... Most of my walking is on asphalt or concrete so also understand that they arent exactly on a smooth surface most of the time.

The soles are obviously showing signs of wear but there is still decent tread left. The insoles are starting to get a little uncomfortable but still bearable. The exterior fabrics on the shoes are dirty but not overly worn out. I do welding on occasion and there are a few small holes on the tops of the shoes where molten metal has burnt through (that feels good on the feet...), but the holes haven't even enlarged over time.

Overall I would say that I only recommend these to those who want ridiculously long lasting, comfortable, and durable shoes. If you want less, look elsewhere.

They may cost a little more than the discount shoes at big 5 but they last much longer than anything else I have tried.

column14:
Vivobarefoot is known for their running, hiking, and lifestyle/dress shoes for minimalist/barefoot lovers.

I've own the Dharma, Jay, and Gobi from Vivobarefoot and love them all. This new Mata, which costs more than the Dharma and Jay of previous years is a mix of the two. It has a sleeker look than the split toe Dharma, but the minimalist construction and firmer leather of the Jay. It has a very minimalist construction and is very lightweight and flexible.

I wish that the sole wasn't the color of fishing gear (all black would be appreciated), but it's an overall nice looking shoe.

The sizing is a bit on the smaller side, perhaps one EU size smaller than expected.

column6: KEEN Women's Whisper Sandal
column14:
I purchased these to wear when hiking around mountains and streams/rivers. They were perfect for my needs. The pair I received fit true-to-size, though I did try on pairs in different colors in stores, and I noticed that they some colors fit differently (a bit on the small side), so it seems it is not always consistent. The "parachute" color is a deep, grape-y purple, which I liked. In this color, my normal size fit, though I was concerned at first that they were a tad short. It felt like there was no room in the heel to spare at all. After wearing them around my house a bit, I realized that I was feeling the contoured ridge on my heel- not the edge of the shoe. I have worn them many times now, and the fit is truly perfect. However, in another color (I think it was black), the pair in my normal size rubbed my toes (which does not happen with my purple ones), but the next 1/2 size up was too big. So that color would not have worked. Since I was fortunate enough to receive a pair that fit perfectly, I am very happy with these shoes. They are very easy to get on/off and adjust with the bungee. They were comfortable to wear on hikes, but I also just wore them around trekking town. They feel like sneakers, but keep my feet nice and cool. I like that the tow guard gives some coverage, but doesn't encase too much of my toes. I did not do too much in the water with them yet, but they were fine for what little I did in small streams and riversides.
I purchased these for myself after my child had been wearing her pair for a few weeks and just loves them. She calls them her "summer sneakers", and that really is a good way to describe them, since they have much of the functionality of sneakers but the coolness of a sandal. I usually wear flip-flops all summer, but I have found myself throwing these on when I would otherwise have worn a sneaker. I really enjoy these, and am thinking about getting another, lighter color so I can have a pair that would work with other clothes, too.th other clothes, too.

column13: ALMOST an amazing boot but FAILS in functionality.
column14:
My biggest problem with the shoe is the WIDE entrance, non-rigid tops, and the unnecessarily large heel. It feels like a woman's heel and even looks a bit pointy. It's stylish to a degree but it begins to become painful because of the loose opening. Depending on how you walk, you'll find yourself hitting everything heel first in a very annoying tap-dancing way. This process begins to put tension on your heels and will tire you out. It looks good but it doesn't function well.

CONCLUSION:
I don't recommend this model and I think you'll find comfort in a different one. In my opinion, it begins to have feminine aspects that will eat at your conscious because you want to look good and feel good in quality boots.

column6: Bogs Men's Eugene Waterproof Nubuck Leather Shoe
column13: Tighter than Scrooge's purse strings and flatter than Marky Mark's abs
column14:
Other reviewer's don't lie, the opening is so tight it takes some force to fit your foot in. On the flip side, they don't have that floppy feeling that other laceless boots or shoes have. Getting them off isn't as bad as I expected although there is no heal to lever against so I'm sure that the sole will begin peeling loose in short order, especially since it is glued on and not sewn.

Two big gripes with this boot: Unless you are Captain Hook, good luck getting a digit in the pull strap. I mean really, who checks this stuff at the factory? It's all I can do to get the tip of my finger in, I'm going to have to fab up a metal hook to aid in putting these on. The absence of a front strap is a major oversight.

Gripe number two is there is zero arch support in this shoe. Did they use retired NYPD flat foots to design this thing? They are decent to wear for a couple hours and there is so little room inside I don't think you could get away with adding an insert or arch support.

So to sum it up, for $50 it's a pretty decent boot that would work well for short stints of light wear. You will probably spend more time writhing on the floor trying to don and doff them than you will actually wearing the darn things. FYI I'm from the city of Eugene of which the boot is named so I am eminently qualified to review it I think!

column6: Merrell Women's All Out Soar Walking Shoe
column14:
LOVE these. I bought them for their minimal drop (not quite zero but close) for my HIIT training and Squats. I originally sized up from 8 that i tried on in the store to the 8.5 (they didn't have in store) as generally buy in walking shoes since I buy a 9 in running shoes - well that didn't work so well for the HIIT, Lunges, or boulder hopping because they were way too big. I then bought the 8s and probably could use an 7.5 for my desired purpose since I prefer to wear without socks. I wear my larger ones for running now and my smaller ones for things that I don't want my feet to slide. These are designed to be washed in washing machine and worn without socks if you desire. They are MINIMALIST shoes with good tread. I have super high arches. These do not have arch support at all. I have come to the realization that arch support might be damaging my feet's ability to support themselves well. I was told my feet would probably hurt when I first started since Im not used to minimalist shoes. They did not (I go barefoot a lot). I have narrow heels and wide forefoot. these have a large toebox. I have the Tahoe color and the Pink/orange ones
For size reference: I wear a 7.5 in dress shoes, a 8-8.5 in walking shoes, and a 9 in my Brooks running shoes.

column6: KEEN Men's Voyageur Mid Hiking Boot
column14: Second pair of Voyageurs for me: at 230#, in my 60s, my job as a mental health counselor has me scrambling up & down multiple flights of stairs across several of Southeastern Massachusetts' tired old milltown landscapes. With concerns for over-pronation, popped kneecaps, & the awful allure of broken hips behind each potentially incapacitating work-a-day overexertion, these boots had better be reliable and maximally comfortable; they are. (Due to these concerns, I tend to buy men's boots; perhaps I'm wrong, but it seems as if they're made better than women's. Can't say if it's so, since I haven't had the money to try women's as well.) Very lightweight, sturdy, well-ventilated & fairly quick-draining, its mid-height securing the ankle, with excellent traction even over oil-slicked pavement (I do hope that was oil...), the Voyageur has non-abrading long-lasting laces with one upper set of gripper lugs to set your desired tension at the ankle. The only negative aspect I've seen is relatively quick lug wear, with a tendency I think most Keens have of some glue-detachment at the sides of the sole. Since I'm rather "thrifty", my expectations of getting several years of 18 hour wear might be unreasonable.

They have broken in a lot better than I expected (yes I know Vibram's take time to break in, but based on my previous experience with Vibram's and initial fit, I didn't have much hope for these) and are now fairly comfortable, though still big in the toe box. column14: Bought these boots for my son to take on a Scout trip to Philmont Scout reservation.  Purchased a month before the trip so he had a little time to break them in.  They worked well on the few small hikes we took.  But after hiking the first 2 days of his 14 day trek @ Philmont the glue on the outside edge of one of the boots started to come apart.  SO I only gave the boots a 4 star rating.  They did hold up for the rest of the 77 mile trek and Amazon has agreed to a return, (So thank yo Amazon) He did not have any issues with the boots other than the glue coming off on the outside edge.  The bottom of the treads look great and there were no issues with the stitching. I will buy these again.  He told me the arch support wasn't the best but they were still very comfortable for his trip.

column13: Almost as good as my old Tevas

The toe area of the footbed is MUCH wider (at least an inch) even though the rest of the footbed seems similar to my old pair. 2. The triangle "link" near the pinky toes do not have a piece of material underneath like my old ones. So far, this hasn't been an issue with blisters or anything, but my toes are just more "aware" of that link being there. These are definitely more comfortable than the Barracuda style I bought off of Zulilly last year (knowing that my old ones were bound to go sooner or later)
