column6: KEEN Women's Venice H2 Sandal
column14:
Reviewing Keen Venice H2 Sandal. I don't normally write reviews, but under the circumstances, I feel compelled and hope this helps someone else. I appreciate the information from other people found in reviews, and I always look at them before ordering online.

I have worn these sandals for about 10 years, and do swear by them. I wear an 8.5. In any other shoe I have to order Wide Width. My situation is very bad feet; wide, with bunions, bunionettes (the bulge on the side of the little toe), high, arthritic and painful insteps. I have had surgery to repair one foot, requiring a lengthy process to get back to normal activity. I have several screws and a steel plate in that foot, both in the big toe and the top of the mid-foot. Needless to say, my shoes are important and it's very difficult to find ones that I can wear.

This shoe gives a good amount of support, is wide enough for my foot, and has a high round toe box. And, you can wear it in the water, to protect your feet. It can go in the washing machine to clean. We do cycling vacations, and I love these shoes to ride my bike. They have the protection for your toes, but are much cooler than wearing sneakers. I have walked all over Europe in these shoes. I own several colors. And they last and wear well. I definitely recommend them. The other Keen styles do not work for me, but I wish they did.

If anyone reads this and knows of some dressier flat shoes with a wide width and a high toe box I would love to hear about it.

column6: Salomon Women's XR Mission Running Shoe
column13: Salomon is now my alternative hiking footwear brand!
column14:
I bought these primarily for summer hiking, not trail running. I wanted a lighter, more ventilated shoe. These definitely fit the bill, and the color really pops! I first wore them one day to see how they felt, then went on a 9 miles hike with my Sunday group. No added insoles, although I had been using a memory foam insole in my Vasque hiking shoes. They felt great, even the long downhill at the end of the hike didn't mash my toes!

I was a bit concerned about ordering the correct size. I wear a 8.5 in regular sneakers, and a 9 in hiking boots. According to the Salomon size chart (on their website) I should get 8.5, so I did, even though many reviewers said they ran large. At first my left big toe felt too close to the front edge, but if I make certain my heel is set firmly against the back before tightening the laces, they fit just fine. They are comfortably snug from heel to mid-foot, then they open up to a roomy toe box.

The Quick-Lace system works OK, and there will be no more untied laces when hiking through underbrush!

Although I am happy with Vasque boots, I will definitely consider purchasing Salomon boots in the future!

column14:

I expected the Cole Haan product quality would be better than other, lesser priced, retail shoes that are available, which would justify the cost. This has not been the case, however, and it took two pair to teach us this lesson.

The problem is that the sole has worn through on both pair quite quickly, much faster than any other shoes that he owns, and he owns a lot of shoes. If you look up on Cole Haan's website, they do offer a repair service, but it costs almost as much, or as much, as a new pair of shoes. Tack on shipping and you'll be paying more.

I am highly disappointed in these shoes and will not be purchasing any more shoes from Cole Haan.

column6: Five Ten Men's Anasazi Verde Climbing Shoe
column13: Great shoes, even for a beginner.
column14:
These are my first pair of climbing shoes. I bought them at my street shoe size. I have somewhat wide feet, and these shoes fit great both length and width wise. Their shape is slightly asymmetric in the toe area, I can sometimes feel my toes are squeezed and hurt slightly if I wear them more than an hour. However, the rubber on the heel section of the upper sole of these shoes are shaped aggressively, and cut in to your ankle at first. After some break in, it becomes better. And I found that you should not over-tighten the laces, this also helps to prevent discomfort in the heel area. Among other shoes that I have tried on, I find La Sportiva Solutions feel most comfortable for my feet, at 1.5 size smaller than my street shoes size. This also gives you an idea of how the sizes of these two model compare.

I am only a beginner, but performance-wise I don't have any complaints about these shoes in my three months of climbing in local gym. They stay on small foot holds really well, and are sufficient for heel hooks and toe hooks. I can also smear securely on the wall in the gym, but only with a lot of pressure (I admit that I still need lots of foot work practice). Note that the sole of the shoes is almost flat with no or very little downturn. The material is also relatively soft, so that you can feel the holds and practice your foot muscle. I think although these shoes are not specifically designed for beginners, but it definitely works for my need as a beginner.

column6: Merrell Women's Terran Convertible Sandal
column14: Hats off to Merrell!  This is a great sandal!  I bought them in brown and was so impressed after the first time I wore them that I immediately ordered them in black.  The shoe has really good arch support and the inner sole molds to your foot after a couple of wearings.  It is very flexible and extraordinarily comfortable.  The inner lining is suede-like and the the outer sole has a hiker-like gripping rubber.  There are 3 Velcro straps for adjustment across the ankle and heel, so you can get the fit and comfort just how you like it.  I like the shoe too because even though it is not dressy, it is not clunky or chunky either and can be worn with all but the dressiest things.  They run exactly true to size.  Excellent value even at full price--better yet at the 40% off I paid.

column6: Oakley Carbon Fiber Men's Storage Case Fashion Sunglass Accessories - Large
column14: This case was an absolute disappointment. When the case first arrived, it looked great. The size fit my Oakley Holbrook glasses and it seemed sturdy enough. I leave my case in my car and keep my glasses in it when I'm not wearing them. Simple enough. Sadly, the case did not last more than a few months and the heat from being left in my car completely destroyed my case. The glue that held the case cover on separated and the inside lining of the case separated. There were times when the glue literally was oozing down the side of the case. I live where it can get 95 degrees outside so it's hot, but you would expect a sunglass case to be able to withstand the heat. Do not buy this case if you plan on keeping it in your car. Total waste of money. I contacted the seller (Temecula Motorsports) and they said there is nothing they can do since it's past the 30 day return policy. I figured since they sold a piece of junk that they might return it or give a refund. Nope. Stay clear of this case.

column6: Unisex Toddlers, Kids, Rain Boots Camouflage, Camo Shoes, Military, Army, Lining
column13: Great rain boot for the price.
column14:
These are rain boots I purchased for my toddler - he loves jumping in the puddles. The price point was good and the camouflage look was perfect to match his raincoat.
He likes them and wears them whenever he gets a chance. They look way cool with the clear plastic and the camo print. I try not to let him wear them too long because there isn't any support or cushioning in the boot- but they are rain boots- we didn't expect that from these.

The inside liners come out easily when he pulls his foot out. We have washed them and they survived the washer and dryer with no shrinking (I was shocked!)
We have had these for a few weeks now and the plastic smell still lingers in our closet. I read that in the reviews when we purchased them and didn't realize how strong it would be. If you are sensitive to smells, avoid these. I moved them from my son's room to the downstairs garage closet so we wouldn't smell the plastic everyday.

These were a great price and we would buy them again- for just a rain boot to jump in puddles. That was our intention when we purchased them and we are not disappointed. Would have received 5 stars if it weren't for the smell.

column6: Dansko Women's Lulu Mary Jane Flat
column13: don't judge a shoe because it's orthotic. this one is deceptively stylish
column14:
Orthotic shoes don't have to look like unfashionable old person footwear. With today's technology you can take care of your puppies and still look stylish.

My manager has heel spurs and a swollen foot after working years in retail. I've suggested giving The Walking Company or even Dansko's shoe and boot line a shot to replace her fashionable but unsupported sandals and heels with equally fashionable comfy support. She wasn't buying it and I was met with a scoff and an proclamation that those shoes were for "old people."

Not wanting my own feet to end up like my manager's I decided, well..I can't really speak for the shoes unless I've tried them myself. After reading reviews of the Lulu and many happy wearers claiming they can walk hours/miles in the city with them on without feeling like they're killing themselves by the end of it I was sold. I got these babies in red which happen to look like pink out of the box and up close. No big deal. I prefer pink over red anyway!

I'm usually a boot person because wearing flats makes me feel like there's a thin layer of leather between my feet and the concrete but since owning these Lulus for two days they've replaced my boots quickly and I can say they live up to the hype, price, and claims. I can see myself wearing these indefinitely and I've never heard of or had a mary jane that can provide this much support. I will have to try these out in the city as well.

These cuties can easily be dressed up or down. I wear them with skinny jeans and leggings and the strap is easily hidden. They look like pumps from the front and can be worn with tights or crop pants and shorts for a more feminine look. I can't wait to wear these with a dress. This experience has made me want to check out their boot line as well. My manager's definitely missing out.

column14: I have wanted a Michael Kors purse for a couple years now. Unfortunately, the price is not in my range at the moment! So I started buying cheap $15 - $20 poorly made purses that did not even look that great to ride me over until my budget would allow me my designer purse. I found this MyLux purse after months of frustration and replacements of those other purses, which kept falling apart within a week or too. The MyLux looked designer-esque to me. The color/material looked gorgeous to me and the biggest selling point was the amount of room inside and the stable bottom equipped with pegs so that the purse never needed to touch the surface it was on. This product looked and worked EXACTLY how I wanted! As usual, Amazon delivered it quickly and in perfect condition. I was even impressed with the metal embellishment hanging off the front which has now become my official key holder. I never have to search through my purse looking for my keys again!! I would recommend this purse to anyone wanting a quality, durable, spacious purse that will not only last but looks great too!

column13: Cleared up ankle weakness problems after 3 months of daily wear

Now when I run I'm able to go farther and faster due to my ankle no longer rolling on a regular basis. After a few months of daily wear, I noticed my lower calves and ankles were much stronger; the difference was night and day.

When ordering, order the exact size that your foot is -- KSO EVOs fit sort of like a sock. Put the shoes on toes first, then heel, otherwise the KSO EVOs will stretch out and you'll feel like you're wearing a flipper.

column13: Surprisingly comfy, yet perfect size when folded for travel
column14: I would've given this FIVE stars had the travel bag arrived in perfect condition. I first bought a pair of these while on the road - from a quaint giftshop. I thought they were BRILLIANT! Small, SUPER comfy, fit in a small travel bag - perfect as hotel slippers! So I ordered another pair here at Amazon.com. Yes, they are just as comfy and look great, but I was irked that they came in a travel pouch that had a 4-inch long slash - as if some dufuss with a box cutter had done a sloppy job opening a crate of them. I sent the vendor a letter, but they deflected the blame to Amazon.com. HEY whomever, be careful, willya? Now I have travel slippers that fold, but the case they are to be stored in has a slash across it, and will likely tear WIDE open after a couple uses. NOT HAPPY. I will just have to go buy a cosmetic case that I can stuff these into for travel. Cuz it is amazing that they fold in half, yet unfold and are completely comfortable (not flimsy or with any detectable "fold" feel to them). Would LOVE to order more when the colors and sizes are replenished. HOWEVER, do order a size up if you are at the high end of the scale. A 7-8 is NOT big enough for someone who needs an 8.

column14: Because I have plantar fasciitis and have to be very careful with my choices in footwear. These Dansko sandals are comfortable and absolutely beautiful. They pair perfectly with a pair of jeans, a skirt or dress. They give a dressy touch to any outfit without being over the top. I am very impressed with how comfortable these are. Like every pair of Dansko's I own (which is quite a few) the arch support is fantastic. These are a beautiful vibrant red which makes them a great accessory. The strap around the ankle is adjustable. The straps across the top of the foot are not, however given that they are leather, they will stretch and break in after wearing them a few times. I give them 5 stars for comfort and 5 stars for looks.

I just bought another pair of Magnums that resemble my old pair of Magnum Stealth boots, they are called Magnum Men's Response III 8.0 . column14: Update 7/18/2017 Sad day today ! The strap finally broke because my foot got stuck and I just kept pulling instead of taking my foot out of my flip flip and unsticking the flip flop from the floor ...  oh well .. 5 years is not too bad, huh?   I bought a couple of Roxy flip flops (these and the Low Tide ones) but these are definitely my favorite. I find myself wearing them all the time. I shower with them every day ( I am sharing a shower with my roommate and prefer not to walk barefoot) and they have been holding up pretty well for 2.5 yrs now (pictures are from today).  The Low Tide ones have a cloth strap which makes them soft and cushioned but i feel they are a bit heavy for 24/7 use. These are very light, the strap is made of rubber which means they dry faster too.  I am a size 6.5 and size 7 fits perfectly. My flip flops usually die after a few months of everyday shower use. Even if they don't fall apart, they usually get worn down on one side and my foot keeps slipping to the side which is super annoying so I end up throwing them away. I am a very bad walker so I tend to ruin all of my shoes by wearing them down on one side. But not these flip flops! In these flipflops my foot stays centered and they wear down only slightly in the middle (most likely just being pressed by the weight). I would buy these over and over again! (if they ever fall apart that is, even though there is no indication of that yet :))

column6: Birkenstock Women's Arizona Sfb
column14:
This sandal is great. The initial break in period is a bit of a pain but just go slow and wear them for a few hours each day and within a week or two you should be able to wear them around the clock. My major complaint about these shoes is that bottom soles on my first pair wore down to the cork within 6 months and now I need to look at getting them fixed. They should last way longer than than but in defense of the shoe, I did wear them every single day for those 6 months. I now have a second pair so I don't have to be without while I repair the first.

I did buy both pairs at a local store however. I attempted online ordering of these and they arrived clearly worn. It isn't hard to tell with Birks - after about a day you'll see an imprint of the foot on the footbed. So be careful when buying online and be prepared to send them back because you may end up with a pair that was a previous return.

As for sizing, you'll likely end up wearing a size slightly smaller than what you are used to. I wear a 38 in Birks which is a woman's 7 (I normally wear an 8 in most shoes). My husband wears a 42/men's 9 when he is typically a 10.5. Keep that in mind when ordering,

column14: I really wanted to love these Crocs.  In fact I love most of my Crocs and live in them all spring and summer.  I got these in fuschia and the color is great.  I don't generally care for thong sandals but thought these would be fun to wear during the day and even for casual dinners on our upcoming cruise.  Now, I'm not sure I will even bring them along.  As other reviewers wrote, I too had some minor discomfort with the rear piece poking and rubbing my ankle.  It also does not sit on the middle of the back of the ankle and feels like it turns in towards the inside just off center and enough to feel weird.  Adjusting the strap does not seem to help with this problem.  If it doesn't rub at the ankle then it pulls on the inside of my toe from the thong.  Now, if I'm lucky and hit it just right, with my heel pulled slightly back to rest in the cradled portion of the rounded heel and my toe just right around the thong, I can actually go a few strides without incident.  But of course, they don't stay like that as you move and so after a few steps I am in pain and trying to grip and readjust my stride which is too much work to make a shoe feel comfortable.  It either is or it isn't.  I wear a 7.5 in regular shoes but have always been fine with a 7 Croc.  These seemed a hair large with the front just a tad longer than I'd like for a sandal so maybe the whole thing was just off to begin with.  I wore for about 3 days in a row to give it a fair chance and to break in as other suggested but it just isn't working for me.  I may continue to wear casually for very short periods but these will not be my go to Crocs.  Had no problems with the rivets so far and have been very careful to secure those areas when putting on and taking off.  Only time will tell.  Update- so I really couldn't believe I'd met a pair of crocs I didn't like.  Well, actually I'm sorry but I can't stand the original clog crocs!  All the sleek flats and my one winter pair with liner- love love love.  So I really couldn't believe how badly these were for me and I gave them another chance.  Wore them another couple of days and I am coming around.  I guess I've built up a callous on the back of my ankles and they no longer rub.  Every now and then the thong piece pulls the wrong way but for the most part these are now working for me.  Maybe they will go on vacation with me after all.  But I will be careful and wear a more tried and true pair on port days with lots of walking.  These will be great for sea days when I can run back to the cabin and change if needed.  Love the color!

column6: LAUREN by Ralph Lauren Newbury Double Zipper Shopper (Navy)
column14: This company has a lot of pride in their products whether the bag cost $5k or $100 the quality and attention to detail is there. Having already carried a Lauren Ralph Lauren ("Sloan St." satchel) everyday for 2 1/2 years that looks as fabulous today as the day it arrived, I didn't hesitate in purchasing this item.  My bags tend to get packed full but the structure never suffered.  I was shopping for a new one in a different color & considered Dooney, Coach and Kors.  My older Dooney weighs 5 pounds empty so I was really hesitant, but reading reviews on Macy's, Amazon & the official websites I found its not uncommon for these 3 brands to have issues with seams, leather shredding, color peeling etc. and that made my decision for me. I prefer to be safe and not sorry so I went with another Lauren bag. I bought this one in red, can definitely see it's going to be equally stunning in every situation- business appt., lunch with friends, dinner with my love or antiquing with my sisters , no matter if you are dressed up or down this one will work.  Love that about this line.  I also don't want the hassle of having to change bags to compliment my dress.  I'm petite &'this size is perfect, I don't look like I'm playing dress up in my mommys clothes or that the bag is wearing me. The magnetic clasp is substantial and located inside the leather so you never have to worry about losing any part of it.  It really keeps that section secure.  It takes some effort to open the clasp so the contents won't come spilling out when your bag hits the floor upside down.  If you're tired of wasting money on cheap bags or feel like you've been ripped off by higher end bags go with Lauren.  I think you'll be a fan or even a collector for life too.

column6: Propet Stability Walker
column13: Pain-free ALL DAY for the first time in weeks!
column14:
I'm a substantial woman who's worked on her feet all her life. The last few months I've been having some foot problems and it's been a daily ritual to get exactly the right amount of cushioning on the bottoms of my feet to 1) be able to stand for a long amount of time without it feeling like I'm on broken glass, and 2) Keep my feet as 'stress-free' as I possibly can to help them heal. I'd been doing okay but it seemed like it's been two steps forward, one and a half steps back.
Today I received these shoes, and... I WAS PAIN-FREE THE ENTIRE DAY! Yes, they are 'men's' shoes, but they fit right and are sturdy and secure, with good arch support and cushioning, and they don't look 'weird.' (Those of you shopping for shoes for assorted foot problems know exactly what I mean.)
I just ordered another pair, and will order another after that. They will be the only shoes I wear from now on, and the sneakers I'd "PaidLess" for, which despite their name were definitely not my Champions, are in the trash.

column6: Crocs Women's Crocband Jaunt Rain Boot
column14:
I've had these rainboots for almost one year. I've worn them several times.

I think they're pretty cute. I have them in black and like to wear them with colorful knee socks and a dress. The knee socks show above the tops of the boots, creating a fun look.

The white circular rings at the top of the boots are intended to help you pull the boots on. You'll also see spaces for the Jibbitz of your choice, should you desire to purchase those separately.

The boots are lightweight and easy to clean--simply wipe off any dirt. They feel durable, and so far, I have not had any major issues with them. Though, I think I should have purchased the next size up. I wear a 9.5 and bought a 9. They fit, but I can't help but wonder if I would have been happier with a 10.

The main disadvantage is the material. It provides comfort, but it makes my feet hot and sweaty. The boots also are stiff. I haven't had any problems walking on flat surfaces, but stairs can be a problem. The boots just do not flex with your ankles.

Bottom line: These are good boots for a rainy day. I just hope you don't have to walk very far.

column6: Dearfoams Men's Color Blocked Corduroy Moccasin
column14:
I bought these so I'd have a nice, reliable, and comfortable pair of slippers to wear around the house and occasionally out to get food (like drive thru where I don't plan on leaving the car)

Pros
1. They look nice. I bought the coffee brown pair and they just look good.
2. These are comfortable. There is some cushioning although I don't expect it to last for years and years of use. They fit my feet very well and don't fall off.
3. The bottoms are rubber soles which adds a non stick element. I also feel comfortable wearing these outside because they do have a "sort of feel like shoes" feel to them.
4. The inside is fuzzy which makes these comfortable to wear with socks or with shoes.
5. Good for squashing bugs on the wall =P
6. They seem well made. I didn't have any loose threads and the stitching feels secure and we'll done.

Cons
1. None yet but I'll likely update my review if things go wrong.

Like other reviewers have noted, these do squeeze your feet a little bit so they're probably not for people who need wide slippers. They also provide little arch support but I knew this buying them. They're slippers, not running shoes =)

Overall, I love these things and I finally feel like I have a comfortable pair of slippers that's going to last me a while. I've been wearing them since they got here and I've not problems with them whatsoever. Good price too!

column6: Inov-8 Roclite 286 GTX Hiking Boot
column14:
A couple of years ago I bought a pair of Inov-8 Roclite trail runners. After a couple of hundred miles, they were still holding strong even though they didn't quite grip like they used to.

Based on my previous experience, I picked up these boots. Sadly, that was a mistake for a couple of reasons.

First the good.

The Grip - The grip on these boots is second to none. These boots even provide a decent amount of grip on wet rock. I haven't found anything that beats Roclite when it comes to grip.

Lightweight - The boots are about the size of a normal pair of boots, but they weight about 1/2 as much.

The Bad

Size - These are boots are insanely small. Normally I buy my normal size and have plenty of room to spare. I can barely get my feet into these boots. Length wise they are fine. It's the width and height that is out of line. Once you get these on, they do stretch out a little. The sizing issues lead to another big problem.

Cushion - These boots have the least amount of cushion of any boots I have ever owned. These are going to wreck your feet. Normally gel inserts are nice to have. In this case, gel inserts are a MUST HAVE. They will be they only cushion you have. That leads to a big issue. There is ZERO room for gel inserts.

Build - Looking at the boots makes me hesitate. I do not trust the build. They look glued together. Nothing about these boots gives me the impression that they are going to last as long as my trail runners have. I'll test them on a few 10 mile hikes and see how they hold up. I just hope I don't get stuck five miles from the trail head with a busted boot.

Value - Not much. Not many places carry these so it's hard to price hunt. If you pick these up for $150 you will not get value out of them. Go buy some nice boots and avoid these. If you can get these for under $100, you might get some value out of them.

column6: Rush by Gordon Rush Men's Pell Oxford
column14: Bought these shoes at a very deep discounted price on Amazon $59. At 162.00 stay away, there are plenty of better shoes you can get for that price.  Well these shoes fit perfectly and were very light.  The leather looks like corrected grain. These are cemented shoes and cannot be resoled. For the price I did pay I would say these shoes are on par with some of the Calvin Klein, Kenneth Cole, Aldo and cheaper Florsheim shoes. I was looking for flaws since they came from China and found none and was very surprised how well built they were. Shoes are comfortable enough for me to wear all day, I am in and out my car all day for work and do a lot of walking and my feet were not sore by the end of the day. After wearing about 5 times the leather is noticibly creased and I seem to have to polish these shoes after each wear as parts of it looks faded. The leather is kind of thin as well.  I would definitely buy these again for the price I paid as they are cheap but very nice looking disposables and better than any Payless brand. If you are looking to spend full retail might I suggest you look into some higher end Florsheims. Same fit as the Florsheim Jet line but the Florsheims are definitely way nicer with leather bottoms and heels that can be replaced by a cobbler.  Once these shoes are worn down, they are done but so far the wear is slow vs some of my other shoes I wear.

column13: Cute, comfortable, but not durable; run large
column14:
These are super cute and go with any summer outfits. They also seem very comfortable since the toes are well wrapped in. However, this particular style somehow wears out easily if you have an active toddler. I had Jude before this and it lasted longer. Our Craig, however, got a lot of marks on the front and broke within two weeks of use. They were still wearable but looked very old and broken. We purchased a second pair eventually and the front still got worn out pretty easily.

Also, as other See Kai Run sandals, they run large. We worn size 7 SKR flats but had to wear 5 or 6 for these sandals.

I still love them, because I really like the softness of SKR shoes and their designs. They really look great with anything, from play sets to formal clothes. But the trade off is that they are not durable and I kind of can't believe that we need 3 pairs of sandals in 4 months.

column13: I was amazed when I initially tried them on as a size ...
column14: I have been looking for a certain kind of wedge sandal since spring of this year. I found them in this shoe. The shoes are so cute and a get lots of compliments in them. I was amazed when I initially tried them on as a size 10 has rarely ever been too large on me. I am a 10 and can sometimes wear a 9.5, but 10 is really true to my size. I have a normal-wide foot and the toe part of the shoe is a tad loose and wide. Toes of shoes are normally too small for my feet in flats, sandals and heels. If you are truly a 10 they should fit, but know that they could be a tad big. They are not too big to wear or be comfortable though. They are the most comfortable heels of any sort that I have ever worn and they have a good height to them, but are so easy to walk in as they are platform with a wider wedge at the heel which I was looking for. So many wedges have a very narrow heel like regular heels which barely makes them any more comfortable to wear, but these are wide without looking odd. I'm a fan!

column6: Skechers Performance Women's Go Walk 3 Slip-On Walking Shoe
column14: I tried these shoes in the store prior to buying them. I have a flat arch at the front of my feet(making it wide) and my other two arches are fairly high( making the back of my feet narrow). My medial arch ( one between big toe and heel) is exceptionally high. It is extremely difficult to find good shoes for me because of this, even though i'm only in my early twenties. High heels are usually out of the question because my medial arch will not even touch the shoe! I found these and i've been wearing them for over a month and a half now. I have to say out of all the shoes i've tried on the store, these were the most comfortable. Compared to the Go Walk 2, these offer more support for the foot and have better cushioning.They actually conform to my feet easier because of the design on the bottom. The individual circular parts of the sole actually press into the crevices of your feet making it very comfortable, while the rest of the sole just adds a bit of cushioning.( To see what i'm talking about look at the pictures. You'll see some from the middle to the top of the toe area that looks different from the rest of the sole. That the main thing that is different from the go walk 2,which adds a little more comfort and well worth the price difference in my opinion. ) The reason I gave them four stars was only because i'm starting to feel some foot pain again after standing on them all day. To remedy this for a few more months, I am getting a very thin insole with gel to relieve some of the pressure that has begun to accumulate on the heels of my feet and the lateral part of the distal portion of my feet( towards pinky toe). This I know is from how I walk and the material at the bottom of the shoes makes them slightly easier to wear out then harder soled shoes. After I few more months I will buy another pair to keep the support and shock absorption at healthy level for my feet( we should change out shoes anyway to help our joints and feet to stay healthy!) However, for theprice they are excellent! If you are not able to dish out a few hundred bucks for shoes or are considering other shoes that are below 100 dollars, these are where to look! Obviously try to find a store that sells them and try them on first if you have the option. For the men's shoe it was way to wide in the back of the foot for my boyfriend, while for me it was perfect even with my narrow heel. For my budget I will definitely buy them again once these wear down!  Note: For those looking for shoes that are very hardy and will last on rough surfaces, these shoes are not for you. These shoes have a softer sole. This makes great for casual jobs or walks because it cushions the foot and does conform to a good degree to all feet types. Because of this softer, squishy sole they will not hold up well over time on rugged surfaces ( they are not made for that).They are also very lightweight and are more of a slip on type of shoe. (Again, this shoe is not made for the industrial work environment.) They are also not very slip resistant, but I have noticed that water doesn't seep in the top of the shoes of the black colored version I have. Also I'd like to not that because of the design they are not made for custom orthotics or any large insole, because you simply won't have room! I hugs my feet already( in a good way) and adding a bulky insole will not only hurt my feet but mostly likely won't fit in the shoe before even adding my feet in it. That is why i'm only getting a very thin insole to put inside it. Overall great shoe just keep in mind these things when purchasing!

column6: ASICS Men's Matflex 4 Wrestling Shoe
column14:
I purchased these shoes for Krav Maga, Patriot Knife Fighting, and Ketsugo mat work. I got my shoes today and unfortunately will have to return them for a larger size. Normally I wear size 11, so after reading the many reviews, I went up to size 11.5 which is too small. The width is somewhat narrow, but not so much that it wouldn't work for my needs.

I'm ordering the size 12 today and will return the 11.5. As far as construction and looks... well made shoes and i didn't see any flaws or problems that would cause them to fall apart or anything like that. ASICS puts out a good product, but if you want these, go up a full size.

An update: I got the size 12's and the length is great, however, the width of these shoes is very narrow in comparison to my normal shoes. I can still use them and so far they are comfortable enough, however, if you have a wide foot then these are not the shoes for you.

column6: Patagonia Men's EVERlong Trail Running Shoe
column14:
These are great running shoes at a rocking price. Just what I was looking for.

I just ordered last week and got within a few days with the free shipping. Very fast, and two days before anticipated delivery date. I've only had one run in them, but first impressions are:
- they felt just a little large in the toe when I first put them on as there was more space than I expected there. However after my first run I'm convinced I got the right size and that a half-size smaller would probably be a tad too small. so I'm happy with the size.
- very light. you can barely tell they are on.
- true that they are incredibly comfortable out of the box and make it easy to run. This is great. but it doesn't seem they are great for arch support.
- the main 'body' of the shoe is comprised of like a 'mesh' - this is great for keeping the shoes light, but know that your foot is going to get wet if the shoe gets wet... it's nice that they are so breathable, but probably not going to be the best bet in wintertime...
- the sole doesn't have 'cleat' texture but is flat. the material of the sole is great and I noticed right away when I went on a slick, wet floor, they held firm. Very nice. good traction that is probably a little better for running on the road rather than the trail; but great for both from what I could tell today.

For quality trail-running shoes, these would be very tough to beat at their current price on Amazon. Hard to gauge how long they will last; due to the light weight of the shoe, they almost feel flimsy and prone to falling apart. But they are obviously good quality and live up to the reputation. Kudos to Amazon for the super fast free shipping.

column6: G By Guess Jogger Textile Sneakers Shoes
column13: Light, airy, highly cushioned, comfortable, fit true to size (forwide-feet individual)
column14: I'm very happy with these sneakers and highly recommend them! They are light, airy, highly cushioned, comfortable, and fit true to size (to me as a wide-feet individual). I had a pair in size 6.5M (width: 3-3/8 inches; length: 9.5 inches), and found that they fit me very well both width and length. I normally wear hiking shoes in size 7M-7.5M (in Salomon hiking boots), so for this pair of sneakers to fit my wide fit means they will be a little wide for individuals who usually wear medium-width shoes. Therefore, if you have wide feet, I'd recommend to go true to your sneakers size or 1/2 a size down (if you plan to wear them with thin socks). If you have medium or narrow feet, I'd suggest to go 1 size down. The design of the toe elongates my feet; even though they are wider than average sneakers, they do not make my feet look wide. In addition to that, the textile upper is light and soft, which makes them quite comfortable to wear. The pink color accent is more like a hot/ neon pink and very pretty, not purplish like in these photos.

US	24808554	R2Z2OK9W1YJHQ7	B001Q03JVA	124064377	Scarpa Men's Zen Multisport Shoe	Shoes	4	0	0	N	Y	Solid Scrambling and Approach Shoe	The Scarpa Zen is a technical shoe squarely targeted to the user who demands higher performance than a soft trail running shoe for difficult rock scrambling and low grade climbing (class 3 to low 5), especially for multi-day backcountry routes where the weight of the pack creates more stress during foot flexion. That said, this is a climbing shoe more than a trekking shoe and its performance is optimized accordingly and it climbs up to mid-5th class rock well with good technique.<br /><br />For trekking expect some discomfort in the thinly padded forefoot over the course of high mileage days but otherwise the down-to-toe lacing and reasonable roomy toe box (at least for a scrambling shoe) allows the hiker with well-conditioned feet all-day comfort if the terrain is rough/rocky (which means lower mileage/speed vs. easy trail).<br /><br />This is among the stiffer approach shoes out there (hence it's climbing/edging performance) which has the benefit of being a very effective shoe in scree, traversing on steep sidehills, snow, and when paired with crampons for the incidental glacier crossing.<br /><br />So why 4 stars instead of 5? Antiquated use of leather in the upper. I'd prefer newer, lighter, and less water absorbent materials, such as the incredible woven fabrics used by Scarpa in their lightweight mountain boots like the Marmolada.	2015-08-05

column13: Adequate and bargain for stage/dance but don't expect them to last long
column14: I bought these shoes to wear for my ballroom dance lessons. The shoes are very comfortable, fit perfectly (I wear 7.5, regular)  and should be good for at least 8 to 10 lessons.  They look nice but as mentioned in previous reviews, the soles and heels will not last very long.  I have only worn them once on a hardwood floor for 30 minutes and the heel is already worn down.  I am happy with the purchase because for the price, if I can get 10 uses out of it, it will be a bargain.  I would not wear these outside on the sidewalk as that would wear out the soles and heels very quickly.  I think these shoes are for stage use only.  As for arch support, I don't need it but if you do, you may need to put an insert in.

column6: Michael Antonio Women's Tia Dress Sandal
column14: I just received these shoes and the sizing is more off than any other Michael Antonio shoe I've bought. I'm usually a size 8 but I bought a 7.5, according to the size chart, because reviews did not mention the sizing being too off. Well, with these shoes I will need a size 7, 6.5, maybe even 6. A whole 1 to 1 1/2 size difference is way too big of a deal, especially if you're not well informed. They will be returned, though beautiful & comfortable. I'm not sure about rebuying, hoping to get the right size. Either way, size 7 is sold out and they don't carry a 6.5. (-_-)   According to Michael Antonio size chart, the size 7.5 fits a foot, from heel to toe, that's 9.5 inches long. As you can see in the photos, the size 7.5 was NOT 9.5 inches in length, but 10 inches. I would recommend measuring your foot, minus half an inch, then buy the size that matches those measurements.

column6: Calabria Reading Glasses - 720 Flexie
column13: Light as a feather! Painlessly stay put!!
column14:
These are probably the best reading glasses purchase I've ever made. I love the frame's black matte color, which I've found difficult to locate, especially in a pair of inexpensive reading glasses.
And since we're talking about the frames, they're also the lightest, most comfortable pair I've ever owned - bar none. You know how some glasses (especially the inexpensive "off the shelf" variety) feel like they're going to deform the ridge of your nose because of the way they pinch, and/or because they have those incredibly uncomfortable pads that sit on (and often slide down) either side of your nose? NOT THIS PAIR!! And by the time we've reached the age to need them 24/7, some reading glasses have caused a painful indentation/groove/deformation above and behind each of our ears - NOT THIS PAIR of bad boys! Because they are SO flexible AND so light, they will fit practically ANY shape/size head - and will do so comfortably and painlessly - and will not deform the bridge of your nose or behind your ears. And yet they still stay in place, hour after hour!!
Many reviews have mentioned the fact that you can comfortably wear these glasses while in bed reading and watching your iPad or TV, and it's true. And they do this frustration free, holding the perfect position for reading/viewing pain free as long as you're able to stay awake.
It may sound cliche, but you really do forget you're wearing them.
These are definitely on my list to buy a second and third pair!

column14: These are great for my feet. I have zero arch and these are superb in the way that they provide me with a much better posture for my feet & ankles. I don't have narrow or super wide feet...but these are perfectly wide enough considering I have no natural arch and over-pronating issues. I was skeptical about the claims & surprised when they actually corrected the way I walk. I watched a QVC video that advertised them & the guy said if you need a half size to order a down...he also said that these particular flip flops were for people with medium to wide feet. I have large feet and didn't want to risk them being too short/small or the return process, so I ordered a size up instead and they fit my feet perfectly. So, that'll be your call based on your feet. There's a tip that comes with the shoes that advise that if you're not used to this type of shoe with all the orthotic technology, it's better to wear them a little at a time until your feet gets used to them. Take that advise. It's going to hurt...but now, I'm able to wear them anywhere that requires a lot of walking and my feet much, much better wearing these compared to my other flat, non-orthotic flip flops. I feel more secure concerning stability with these.

column6: Skechers Performance Men's Go Walk 3 Slip-On Walking Shoe
column13: EGGSHELL CONSTRUCTION; RETURN AT YOUR OWN COST; KEEP LOOKING
column14:
I wish I had read the return/exchange policy details more carefully. Cannot exchange, only return. And while the seller states a commitment to completely satisfactory transactions, returns are at the expense of the buyer. CAVEAT EMPTOR / buyer beware. Shoes can be funny size-wise, fit-wise, and other-wise. And that they were.

Since, it is possible to purchase them online elsewhere and return them, if you choose to, at no cost, it makes no sense to buy them here. I wish I had shopped more carefully. These shoes fit too large, and the construction reminds me of a carton of eggs. Nothing special, nothing great, not very sturdy. I kept them because I hate paying for returns.

The return policy is clearly stated so my bad for not reading and considering that policy more carefully. But whether stated or not, I think it is a lousy policy. I bet you agree. The shoes are not lousy, but they are not great. They are not good. They are less than satisfactory, and I would not buy them again.

I recommend neither the shoes nor the seller for the reasons discussed.

column14:
At first I thought these were too pointy for my taste and not as comfortable as I would like, but then I had a change of heart when I tried them on with clothes and looked in the mirror. To me, they have a look that is both a classic sophisticated office style, with a hint of vintage rock and roll. It's not my typical style of shoe, but I like the heel a lot on these, the height, and the somewhat vintage styling. I also don't love buckles and zippers on my shoes, so I like the simplicity. Also, I wanted something more sophisticated.

They aren't uncomfortable, they just aren't comfort shoes, but I wore them all day at work and rode my bike home in them after and had no feet problems. So, long story short, they are a keeper. column6: Reebok Men's Quickchase-m
column13: Affordable, Comfortable, Nice Looking Shoes! I'd buy another pair.
column14: For the money I was highly impressed. I am really a fan of these shoes. The all over material is HIGHLY breathable, they are lightweight and really not bad looking at all. I really like the "Memory Foam" insoles that come with these shoes. The insoles are stitched into the bottom of the shoe and are literally like the memory foam you would see on a high end bed. The material wrapped around the foam on the insole is like a neoprene so it is smooth and it really does form to the contours of your feet. I use these for work and you can tell a BIG difference when you are standing. When you start walking and moving around the foam adjusts to your foot as you walk. It's an interesting feeling but provides comfort and support unlike other more expensive shoes that I own. I would absolutely buy another pair. Since they breathe so well my feet don't get sweaty or musty which is always a plus. For the money you should give them a try. I'm sure you will like them.

No more New Balance products for me.

column6: Vionic Jon Men's Slip-on Orthotic Sandal
column13: Very Cheap Quality Thin-Leather Foot Straps That Easily Stretch
column14:
My only complaint about these high-priced sandals - The upper & lower foot straps are 'cheap-thin-leather' sewn to a synthetic backing that stretches-a-lot over a short period of time of use...and/or if the sandals become Wet. Well of course your sandals are going to get wet - that's what sandals are for, to wear around Water.
In my opinion, a $100 pair of sandals should have a durable and heavy quality foot strap to prevent stretching. The Vionics FAILED on this very important issue. Here is the damaging issue: The straps on these Vionics 'stretched-so-much' that the Velcro (which secures the upper strap to the lower) OVEREXTENDED it's reach to the lower Velcro-Strip so much that I could not fasten the Upper Strap around my foot. (there was no Velcro to fasten to on the bottom strap) So, I went to the local shoe-repair-man and had New and Longer Velcro-Strips sewn on the straps so I could fasten the upper strap to the lower.
Bottom-Line: These $100 Vionics are made with cheap-thin-stretchable-leather-straps, and are NO-Match for Quality of The Sperry Top-Siders at 1/2 the price of these Vionics.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Elite 800X Premium Fully Wireless Gaming Headset - DTS Headphone:X 7.1 Surround Sound - Noise Cancellation- Xbox One, Mobile Devices
column14: EDIT:  My comments below about a similar Turtle Beach Headset that I feel is better.  I'm not going to be the person to give this a 1 star simply because it didn't meet every possible expectation.  But as a Turtle Beach customer for many years, let me give some warnings about this headset.  The most obvious item is the price tag... $299 US Dollars is something to consider.  It simply is not worth it.  This headset is not garbage, but in my honest opinion it's nowhere near Elite as the title suggests.  Let me see if I can explain:  Sound Quality:  It's good.  Claims to be 7.1 surround and I can't knock it.  But I also can't say it's better than any other stereo headset from Turtle Beach.  Just no way to really simulate true surround sound in speakers that are less than an inch from your ears.  So I'm not one to say the premium $ is well spent here, but the sound isn't bad either.  I will say that the sound isn't very loud, but that may be an XB1 limiting factor here.  Not that I need to have the sound louder, but the max setting is where I kept it when playing Batman Arkham Knight and any softer would have been a huge negative.  Mic:  This is an oddity for sure.  I tested this while leaving voice messages over XBL... playing back the recording sounded great.  But testing via party chat my friends said it wasn't as clear (I was understandable but sounded distant).  This is apparently an issue they are trying to fix via firmware.  At purchase, I was informed via online that firmware updates were suspended.  Maybe it will get better, but the lack of boom mic here will most likely be an issue going forward.  Not having a mic in front of your face is awesome, but the point is to have the best quality possible... that's just not gonna happen with a "built in" mic.  Mic Monitoring:  I'm sorry, but no idea why this has gotten worse over the years.  I had a Gen 1 Turtle Beach headset for the original Xbox.  I was so hyped to have an all in one headset, but it was veryapparent right away how hard it was to talk when I couldn't hear my own voice.  By the time the Xbox 360 had arrived, they had fixed this with Mic Monitoring in their (at the time) latest headsets.  I could hear my own voice when I spoke... the mixture of game audio and chat audio was now perfect.  Somehow this got worse and hasn't improved with this "Elite" headset.  Sure, they do have some mic monitoring, but with game volume turned up to a reasonable level it completely drowns out my voice.  Perhaps some people complained that their own voice was too loud and Turtle Beach turned it down... but IMO, BIG MISTAKE!  I want to hear my voice and my teammates as well as game audio loud and clear... that does not happen here.  You will get very little of your own voice fed back into the headset and that is really a bummer!  Comfort:  Another con for me.  I have a head that is somewhat skinny... taller than it is wide for sure.  And yet these tend to be firm and push in on my head.  No so much that they hurt, but I wouldn't call them comfortable either.  I can't help but wonder how they feel for people with more round heads.  Overall:  Sure, I'm definitely going out of my way to point out the negative.  There are positives for sure, but if you are considering spending $299, you probably already know the good things about this headset and they are all true (blue tooth, android app, presets, etc.).  Like I said in the beginning, I'm giving this 3 stars and not completely trashing it... but I am also returning it.  It's just not up to $299 level (and from what I hear, neither is the Astro A50).  Note:  I had some connectivity issues that led me to believe mine was defective, but that is not part of this review.  In the end, I guess the best way I can describe this headset is that if money were no object, I still wouldn't be completely satisfied with this headset.  There are just too many things (particularly mic monitoring) that Turtle Beach did better almost 10 years ago.  So if money is an issue, I simply cannot recommend.   Update - Comparison to the Turtle Beach Stealth 420X:  IMO the 420X is a much better deal than the Elite 800x.  It is lacking some of the features, but at half the cost I am perfectly fine with no bluetooth connectivity, simulated surround sound, and a bunch of presets I'll never use.  The Stealth 420X has a MUCH better microphone, much improved mic monitoring, easier to use controls, better wireless connectivity, and is more comfortable (probably because it is much lighter and doesn't fit near as tight on your head).  I will most likely post a review of the 420X on that product if you want more details.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column14: There are quite a lot of reviews up here and almost all of them compare Knight to the other Arkham games. Fair enough as those are all good and worth noting. But I couldn't help and compare it with 3 (4 if you count the long-ish DLC) other games—namely the Infamous series.  I love the Arkham series. Fantastic game play and everyone knows Arkham games are magnificent "be Batman" simulators. But for some reason I couldn't help and compare Knight to the more recent PS4 Infamous—another super hero simulator. And there were some things I really missed from Infamous. One is the city inhabitants. Infamous has been populating its cities with bystanders to save (or maim) since 2009. Why hasn't Batman followed suite. As the 2nd game set in the open Gotham City (assuming we count Origins), I expected Knight to finally give me people to save from muggings, ledge jumpers to leap in and reason with, hostages to rescue from costumed villains, etc. None of that was in the game. This Arkham game like all those before it is set in an environment completely populated by villains due to a plot device. Why? I think any perfect super hero simulator provides citizens to rescue.  Of course, having citizens in the city presents the issue that Batman might hurt the citizens or interact negatively with them. Maybe that's why they haven't been there through all these games. Infamous solves that dilemma by offering story paths. Are you a good hero who always saves and never harms citizens or are you the vigilante power unto yourself that the authorities say you are? You get to decide that as you play in Infamous. I don't think I'd advocate going that far with a Batman game—in the end of the day the rules of who Batman is are set somewhat in stone—but I think something like that could have been incorporated. Thugs in Knight run around saying Batman has gotten darker or more unhinged. But I didn't really see that other than in a few cut scenes. Could have been fun to have the option to play a more Dark Knight Batman by not caring nearly so much about how you interact with the citizens and thereby earning the unhinged reputation. Or a more Caped Crusader Batman who is very conscientious of the citizens and clearly keeping it together. The story already provided would have supported that well and could have made for a couple of easy branching endings depending on how much Scarecrow really managed to drag you as Batman down into the muck. All this comes around to choice, which I didn't feel like the game offered quite enough of. Admittedly, story choice is not a feature of the series. But there were several points where I'd wanted to be able to have Batman do A instead of B but the game didn't allow my idea of what Batman (or at least MY Batman) would do to work. You had to follow the rails.  Great game. Beautiful graphics. Engaging story. Plenty to like. Just a few tweaks could have really set it apart from its predecessors.

column6: Mad Catz Arcade FightStick Tournament Edition 2 for PlayStation 4 and PlayStation 3
column13: Things you need to know before you buy this FightStick!
column14:
Things you need to know before you buy this FightStick
If you have a question comment I will try to respond as soon as I can.

Pros
-It works it does what it suppose to do.
-Really good weight to it.
-Cord is long Around 9ft I believe
-Works on ps3 and ps4
-Easy to change art makes the wet/oily look go away depending on type paper you use.
-Easy joystick and button modding without voiding warranty. example(You don't like sanwa and want to use Kuro button or w.e buttons you like as long as they are same dimensions of course. Same with joystick part.)

Cons
-The plexi glass it comes with is really cheap and it gives it almost a wet/oily look to it.(best example I can give is when you try to put new screen protector on your phone and it's not on correctly you can see like the wet marks that it needs to be re adjusted so it can go away)
-The mini tool it comes with to remove the plexi glass and side panels broke after undoing 2 screws. So get your own tool if you are going to mod this there cheap but its nice that they include it other people might have better experience with there's.
-No touch pad

Would I recommend this FightStick Yes since there is only 2 routes to go either Hori($150) or Mad Catz($199.99) (as of now 8/5/2015) I owned many Mad Catz sticks before none failed on me so I am sticking with them. They are also easy/mod friendly without voiding the warranty which is always a plus (can't mod hori sticks or else you void warranty even if one button messes up replacing it voids the warranty its the reason I go with mad catz)

Now all of them will have the wet/oily look to it since the glossy paper is under the really thin crappy plexi glass. If this does not bother you then yes by all means get the FightStick it works. But if it's going to bother you then I would suggest either getting custom art work on it or get the HORI Real Arcade Pro 4. But if looks doesn't matter somuch to you the stick is great works perfectly also 2 years of warranty and you can mod it without voiding the warranty.

Took some pictures to show how the art work looks like if you replace it which for me made the wet/oily look on the plexi glass go away since its not touching the glossy/plastic original artwork.
On one picture I am folding the art work to show it's not paper but a glossy/plastic type artwork.(Note the plexi glass it comes with is around the same thickness of the original artwork which I am bending in the picture so it bends the same way like I said it's really cheap and crappy Plexi glass.

I know I repeated a lot of same things but I want to just get it the word out there. Since I almost didn't buy it since the reviews where so bad but it's honestly just little things that I guess ticked people off.

column14: I got this controller after I received an Xbox One as a birthday present.  It is the newest version so I thought it would be the best. After thinking about it I swapped the batteries from the Xbox One supplied controller.  Now this new controller turned on but my original one didn't.  I thought, "thanks for the cheapo (Duracell) batteries Microsoft".  However, after playing for a few minutes and confirming this new controller did in fact work fine, I shut it down for the day. column6: Pokemon Colosseum
column14: The Nintendo Game Cube has good games like Metorid Prime,and Super Smash Bros Melee,but Pokemon Collaseum is amazing. It's the best RPG pokemon game I've ever played. I highly recommend this to a pokemon fan.  Unlike the cute,simple gameplay pokemon is known for,this game is dark. The storyline is very deep,and full of dark themes. The player is a young boy,he is part of team Snag,a evil team that takes pokemon and use the darkness they have. The young boy teams up with a girl,and the two go around snagging pokemon. You can steal trainers pokemon,if their a shadow pokemon. Shadow pokemon have shadow moves,and are evil. Every battle is a double battle,but it's fun. There are tons of towns and cities. There are pokemon Centers and shops. Tons of trainers you can fight too. This game is well made,and is a great RPG. The graphics are amazing for a pokwmon game. Pokemon Stadium was great,but not as good as Pokemon Colosseum.  Since you can play Nintendo GameBoy games on the Nintendo GameCube,trade your Ruby and Sapphire pokemon onto your game. There are tons of awesome pokemon like Bayleaf in Colosseum,so trade it into Ruby and Sapphire.  There is a Colosseum,battle area,and you can battle pokemon on different modes. Like easy,medium,and hard. There are different teams too. You can even trade your Ruby and Sapphire pokemon into it to fight.  GET THIS GAME!!!! IT ROCKS!!!! STORYLINE AND POKEMON ROCK!!!! HIGHLY RECOMMEND!!!!

column6: PDP AG7 True Wireless Headset for Xbox One
column13: Full Featured and Fully Wireless Xbox One Headphones
column14:
These feature-rich fully wireless Xbox One headphones were a breeze to set up, incredibly comfortable, and produced beautiful sound.

Set up was a breeze. A small USB stick plugs into the Xbox One. Then you turn on the headphones. That's it! These headphones come pre-paired to the USB stick. There are small red and blue lights on the mic that flash as the headphones search for the wireless signal. The light will turn a solid color once the signal is connected.

The power button also functions as a mute button. It is easy to tell if the mic is muted because these headphones utilize a brilliant mic monitoring system: you can hear your voice through the headphones when the mic is on. Headphones without mic monitoring tend to muffle your voice which leads to yelling/speaking loudly. When the mic is muted the mic monitoring is also off, so you can't hear that audible feedback.

A small button at the bottom corner of the headphones toggles between two available modes. The mode displays a color code on the tiny LED on the edge of the boom mic.

"Red" mode is a bass boost. Explosions and rich thunderous sounds are perfect for gaming.

"Blue" mode is pure audio mode. This mode is perfect for watching TV.

The padded headband adjusts for different head sizes. The leather-like ear pads are both soft and reduce external noise. Above the ears, two volume wheels control the overall volume and balance between game and chat volume. The fit was overall very comfortable.

The retractable boom mic worked well. My friends reported a clear voice. I really liked that the mic stows inside in the headphone for storage.

The only "negative" I found with these headphones is the same negative I find with all the Xbox One wireless headphones. The headphones work best with a fresh boot of the system, and the signal can be a little touchy if you move your head. Overall, I can recommend these headphones for anyone searching for a fully wireless option for their Xbox One.mmend these headphones for anyone searching for a fully wireless option for their Xbox One.

column6: PlayStation 3D display
column13: THREE out of THREE of these Displays Broke within a FEW months
column14:
First, let us talk about Confirmed Purchase. While I do not have the item listed in my Amazon History, I have already went through 3 (yes, THREE!) of these displays.
The first was purchased from Best Buy. That display broke within 2 weeks.
The problem was that when the power button was pressed, the Power LED will blink a few times, and refuse to turn on the display.
Searching online, it seemed this was some Power Supply issue. So I presumed it was a Power Surge.
I went back to Best Buy and purchased a second one. This time, I plugged it to a Surge Protector.
However, after two months, the display exhibited the same issue again!
Know that the Surge Protector was still healthy, and I had multiple devices plugged into it (some turned on 24/7!), and none of those broke.
Thus, the issue is not a Power Surge.
So, I contacted Sony and they offered the repair it. I believe the one they sent back is a refurbished one, though (different Serial Number).
You know the story by now. Within a short amount of time, that replacement had the same issue again.

So what's the conclusion?
Either it's extremely poor quality control, extremely bad design, or both.

Do NOT buy this display.
Think about it, what advantages does it even have?
Simulview? Yes, it's a cool technology. But to be honest, it's not that useful. Further, not many games support it.
What about the 3D? Well, there are other options. The 3D-Glasses are quite shaded, and it makes the image too dark. There are better options.

Again, I went through 3 of these displays, 2 from different physical stores (but of the same franchise), and 1 from Sony themselves.
All three broke down within a few months.

column6: PlayStation 4 500GB Console - Batman Arkham Knight Bundle Limited Edition
column13: I'm glad I held off on getting a Playstation 4 to ...
column14:
I'm glad I held off on getting a Playstation 4 to get this system. I'm a huge Batman fan and this edition was a must-have in my book. It was well worth the wait and the money. The system is well made and the game is awesome. I found myself using a lot of the entertainment apps, such as YouTube and Netflix. I can also operate both apps using my Android tablet, which is extremely helpful while searching for something to watch. I feel like a wasted money upgrading to a cable box in my room because now I use the PS4 much more. A small drawback in my opinion, is that the PS Store can be a bit slow from time to time.
As for the game, the graphics are amazing and the gameplay is very fluid. The only gripe I have for the game is that the Batmobile is utilized a little too much. I also encountered a glitch during a Riddler race where the Batmobile went through the floor and I had to restart from a save point, this however was a minor inconvenience. The story is pretty good but if you know a little about the Batman franchise, it's easy to guess who the Arkham Knight is.Overall, I'm very happy with my purchase and would definitely recommend it, especially if you're a fan of Batman.

column6: Fallout: New Vegas Ultimate Edition
column13: Hundreds of hours of entertainment for a low cost
column14:
Let me preface this by saying I really loved playing Fallout New Vegas and this review will compare it to Fallout 3 a lot and make some complaints. But that's because Fallout 3 was such an amazing experience that fallout the series is now held up to ridiculously high standards.

Fantastic game. However it always felt (and still does years later) like a really big DLC download that they should never have charged $ 60 for initially. The game was basically fallout 3 with a few tweaks that could have easily been implemented via patches to Fallout 3.

Aiming down the sights was great and much needed, making the gun fighting better and more FPS like. Being able to mod your guns was also a welcomed change.

The story line never felt as epic as Fallout 3's. It's ok but no where on the level of FO3.

I felt that the game could have given you more missions as a legionnaire. And speaking of factions, the game instead of focusing on karma like in FO3 focuses more on which factions you're friends with. So you could be a huge thieving, cannibalizing dirt bag with low karma but the NCR troops will be friendly towards you and say hi because you've attacked Ceaser's Legion. A silly oversight.

As for the DLC for this game, the Dead Money DLC is god awful. There's a mist that permeates large portions of the level and it automatically kills you. There's lots of other things that kill you and some holograms that are invincible. So no matter your level or skill, you'll be dying a lot the first time you go through it. I did and it was very frustrating. The worst is at the end....it's such a tease.

The other DLCS:
Honest Hearts- Not bad, no real interesting items, armor, outfits added
Old World Blues- Rather fun DLC, new interesting weapons, new perks, funny dialogue. This was probably by favorite DLC of the bunch. There's also a lot of upgrades and perks you can earn through this.
Lonesome Road- My second favorite of the DLC. Lots of new weapons and armor in this one. The story was a bit weak and a let down to me based on the build up and mystery of who the other courier was and his whole story etc.

Base game, plus 4 DLC packs and a greatest hits discount? If you've never played this game get it. It's hundreds of hours of entertainment for a super low cost.
I can't wait for Fallout 4.e of the DLC. Lots of new weapons and armor in this one. The story was a bit weak and a let down to me based on the build up and mystery of who the other courier was and his whole story etc.

Base game, plus 4 DLC packs and a greatest hits discount? If you've never played this game get it. It's hundreds of hours of entertainment for a super low cost.
I can't wait for Fallout 4.

column6: Fantasy Life - 3DS
column13: Stop listening to the \its a mix between\" people!!!  Lacks a good reward system, but nice first 40 hours."
column14: Great game, but not for the long haul. The game is awesome for the first 40 hours. Addicting game play, horrible story, but really cute and witty. The issue is after complete the story and DLC, there is really no purpose to continue your grinding for higher ranks unless you just want to do it for fun. You will be able to kill bigger bosses but there is no reward system in place that gives you satisfaction for you having done it. Get this game for 40 hours of fun, to play multiplayer with friends, or play it for 80 hours and realize that the last 40 hours you played you were just lying to yourself saying you were having fun. It like animal crossing, you have so much fun, but then you realize the hard work you have done, and you have a cool house, but then..... then what? Show our friends? Its not enough to motivate you to continue.  This is not a zelda, animal crossing, harvest moon, rune factory game. It does not have puzzles or clever combat like zelda. It is not like AC, it has Minimal house building with next to no character bonding or true com player interaction besides scripted dialog. It is not HM as in you build a farm and raise animals. The game play if finishing quests (hunt 3 of this animal or craft one of these things) and advancing the storyline that is almost entire separate from the gameplay quest. Meaning you can complete the story without doing any of the leveling quests. So quit thinking its like all these games.

column6: Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm 3
column14:
Okay so it turned out to be a really good game. The story mode was so much better than 2. The animation for it was done in such a way it felt more like an anime than the 2 which kind of had them talk and didn't have such dramatic screenshots and stuff. It was like watching the abridged version of Naruto, and it was touching.

I also like the fact I could switch to the Japanese voices which, in my opinion, sounds better and fits the characters better than their English counterparts.

I was disappointed with the lack of freedom you have running around while the story line is going on. You are pretty much forced to stay in certain areas and most of the time the free roam is to go three screens before back to story. It makes sense given that your in a middle of a war and time is technically of the essence and you can't go wondering about, but it was still depressing. I also didn't like that you had a limit to how many times you could use a substitution jutsu before recharging. I guess that keep you and the computer from using it all the time, but it got real annoying when I'm fighting a tough opponent and use them all up very quickly.

Overall, the story line is close to the anime, minus the things they changed at the end cause the anime hadn't gotten far past that, and it was done beautifully. I enjoyed it and had fun, but if you're not a Naruto fan, you probably won't enjoy it as much as someone who does.

column6: Nyko Data Bank
column13: Works great, with a few future suggestions
column14:
Works completely fine. Only issue was heat which I cobbled together a 5v fan to USB which starts up with the ps4. Not a big deal imo since I have extra fans everywhere. Rest mode works fine for me while downloads are going. Basically as long as the hdd is active. I'm using the 4tb sshd. No issues with disk based games.

Those having a hard time with this thing, check your connections. Make sure they're secure and we'll connected. Had an issue at first because I didn't have the hard drive perfectly connected.

Suggestion for future possible product revision, have the entire top slide off, not just the front. And treat the hdd bay as a hdd holder. Ie require at least 2 screws to be screwed in to properly mount the 3.5 hdd. And add heat vents on the top or back.

column6: NVIDIA SHIELD Pro (2015)
column13: Terrific device for streaming 4k video as well as using ...
column14:
Terrific device for streaming 4k video as well as using other Android apps. Also a great gaming platform.

My only complaint is a more general complaint regarding HDCP 2.2 and it's lack of compatibility with 4k TV's built prior to 2015. This was a move that was intended to protect content, but ultimately only upset consumers that had invested thousands of dollars on TV's that can't be used as 4k displays due to this late change in content management. This device will only stream Netflix 4k content at HDCP 2.2 so if your 4k TV only supports HDCP 1.4 you are out of luck. This is typically a hardware upgrade and can't be managed via firmware. In my case, my Panasonic TV offers no solution to this problem.

column6: Nintendo 64 System - Video Game Console
column14:
Ok so here's what's up, I bought this from them. The system for what it is is fine but the controller I received was broken, the stick that is was broken. I emailed them and when they didn't respond I bought a 3rd party controller. Then out of the blue I receive a replacement controller and an email concerning my low rating.

Here's their email:

"Hey bro,

I was just wondering if you got the replacement controller? Anyhow.. If you get a minute, we would really appreciate it if you could remove your original rating (3). I thought your first rating was honest and fair. We are at %88 currently and we are hoping to be in the %90's by the Holiday season.
Much thanks! Eli (Opal's Attic) "

So after they sent me a broken item and I personally bought a replacement for something that should have been right from the start they have the nerve to ask me to raise my rating. Yeah ok...no BRO!

column6: Madagascar - PlayStation 2
column14:
Sometimes, the interesting part of seeing a video game based on a film is that the developers get to have a chance to interpret the movie's story either in a playable manner or in a way that adds additional artistic cues onto what's already set up. Madagascar for the Playstation 2, for example, mainly follows the same storyline the animated film constructed, but at the same time, there are scenes that feature a zebra fighting strange crocodiles, a hippo overdosing on wild chili peppers, a giraffe scaling an old tree that needs to be saved, and a lion taking on the Foosa Leader. Oh yeah - TOTALLY like the movie!

Joking aside, this game allows you to alternatively control zoo animals Marty (the zebra), Alex (the lion), Gloria (the hippo), Melman (the giraffe), and Skipper (the leader of four penguins). The quest revolves around Marty's desires to head off to the wild, what went on during the four friends' escapades at the island of Madagascar, and Alex's psychological need for "steak".

While quite a few movie-based games at the time would utilize footage directly from the films as cutscenes, Madagascar actually decides using its in-game assets for such. The resulting presentation isn't the best, but it works; there are at least a few jokes and gags unique to the game, and the graphics are generally pretty good. The voice acting is also usually up to par, as the substitute actors do a decent job of replicating the movie stars' voice chops, except for King Julien's (lemur leader) actor; he delivers a lousy accent and his lines give Julien a generic native leader personality instead of being that comical dancing cloudcuckoolander we saw in the movie. Also noteworthy is probably Private's (one of the penguins) no-nonsense attitude when you take control of Skipper; I was a bit put off at first, but I've since found it interesting.

As for the gameplay, Madagascar tends to change its mechanics around at various points in the game's 11 levels, but it primarily takes the style of a 3D platformer. You don't get to switch between the characters much, but each of them provides his/her own skills to the table from Alex's double jumping to Gloria's ability to run fast via chili peppers to Marty's leg kicks. I wish there more opportunities for me to just play through a level without a required side-mission or few added on, but as is, I don't mind it too much since they don't really annoy me. Some of the gimmicks utilized in many of the missions come off as arcade-like, but I suppose they get the job done.

The game plays the difficulty rather safely, considering I've beaten the game without getting to see the Game Over screen. However, while the game isn't perfect in more ways than just its easiness, I did enjoy playing Madagascar, and I recommend this title to fans of the movie, those willing to have some platforming cravings satisfied, or both.
