column6: Naruto Shippuden Ultimate Storm Generations
column14:
I give it four stars.

Story
If Ultimate Ninja Storm was the abridged version, then this is the cliff notes. I love that each story opens up with a scene from the anime. It gives an overall story, but mostly just sticks to the fights, but still allows you to have an overall idea of what happened in the universe. They are short as you play through each characters story line. As this game is supposed to be more about the generations of Naruto fighting each other, I found this acceptable even though in Ultimate Ninja Storm I would not have appreciated it as it is supposed to be more about the story. What I dislike about it. WHAT HAPPENED TO THE BLOOD!! If you watch the anime (and I'm not talking about that Cartoon Network and Disney versions that came out that edited so much it became depressing and uninteresting), you know there is blood. They are ninjas. People get stabbed. You have no idea how confusing a fight is if there is no blood. You can't tell if an attacked missed or connected and how much damage there really is. I only played through four story lines, and while I an excuse the gameplay itself not showing blood, I cannot excuse actual clips from the anime (Zabuza's last stand) to be edited. Watching the last stand from Zabuza's fight had be confused on who actually was injured or if he even really attacked them. As I watched the Japanese version of the anime, I knew how it was supposed to be. Since this was made in Japan and kept the Japanese voices, I don't see why they didn't keep the unedited clips. This really irked me, and it lessened the excitement of having real clips in the game.

I haven't played much outside the storyline yet, but I did play some of the tournament stuff. Let me tell you, having sage mode Naruto beat up 12 year old Naruto who is pretty much useless and lacks any skill besides kage bushin no jutsu and rasengan is very very satisfying. In fact having him beat up all of team seven without them landing a single It reminded me of the second chuunin exams when Naruto beat up Konohamaru. I did the same thing with Kazekage Gaara fighting his younger self and siblings. Now this is probably just a me thing, but in a match between Sakura and Sasuke, in what world does Sasuke lose to Sakura (especially when they are children)? I know that it's supposed to be randomly selected so that tournaments have some variety for the player, but come on! That's like saying that TenTen can actually beat someone in the Naruto universe. You can't allow her to have that hope! She's the most useless character in the show, and she beats Neji in the tournament? Like I said that is mostly just me and being a fan of the series, knowing their weakness, strengths, and memorizing the databooks, but it does detract a bit from the tournaments for me though it wouldn't for most.

As a straight up fighting game, it isn't bad. I'm not really into fighting games, but I do love ナルト and I find nostalgia and satisfaction beating characters I don't like or playing characters I love. A fan would probably love it, a non fan, probably not so much. I enjoyed it despite my complaints, and those who has only seen the edited version or stuck to the American version will probably not find any detraction from it.It reminded me of the second chuunin exams when Naruto beat up Konohamaru. column6: Hori (Ps4/ps3 Correspondence) Real Arcade Controller Pro.V Silent [PlayStation 4]
column14:
I have a good deal of experience with joysticks. These are the sticks that I have owned:
- Hori Soul Calibur IV Fightstick PS3
- Hori Real Arcade Pro PS3
- Mad Catz Marvel vs Capcom 2 Tournament Stick
- Hori Ultimate Marvel vs Capcom 3 Arcade Stick

Out of these sticks, I liked the Hori Real Arcade Pro stick the best because I modified it using Sanwa buttons, a Seimitsu spring, a octagon gate, and a bat tip (which I reverted back to ball tip). The second controller would be the Hori Ultimate Marvel because it still included the Sanwa buttons. The Mad Catz controller just clunked out on me so I can't say much about this stick. I been to Evo 2k10 and I was able to do pretty well with my best stick so I do have a great deal of experience with joysticks

The number one issue I have always had with all of these sticks was the clicking of the microswitches when you move the joystick. In my youth, joysticks never clicked, it just has a cheap feel to me. I kind of accepted that microswitches was the in thing of today for joysticks and this is where the Hayabusa controller came in.

Before buying this stick, I was on the fence of first deciding to buy a new stick altogether, and if I did, which one would be the stick to get. I was comparing the Hori Kai, Hori Hayabusa, and the Mad Katz PS4 stick. Mad Katz sticks with the Sanwa buttons I am accustomed to but Hori decides to do something different by developing their own buttons called "kuro". I went to various forums trying to see how people viewed these new buttons and I understand that Sanwa and Seimitsu has been the button of choice for many years without any real reason to improve them. Hori did some work to try to develop a new button and this has been added into this controller. I came across some reviews however of people saying that the buttons squeaks if not pressed in the direct center of the button so I was nervous about this. So while deciding and comparing, I accidently stumbled on this version called the Hayabusa Silent.

What this controller does is add extra parts to the buttons to make the buttons completely silent. But the game changer for me as I was mentioning earlier was the joystick itself. This joystick is a completely different design on the inside from the other Hori and Mad Katz controllers as it uses a optical joystick. That means there is no clicking involved at all in this joystick. Amazingly, I felt very comfortable with the square gate installed in this also. I did some rounds playing KoF using Omega Rugal and I was able to consistently do all of this combos. This controller felt more natural than even my original best controller. It didn't feel as loose to me as my Hori Ultimate Marvel stick which I never modified. It bought me back to the days of when I use to play in the original arcades.

The buttons also felt very good. It was a little stiffer than the Sanwa but I liked it like this. I read that the kuro buttons are supposed to be 60% more durable than Sanwa so I'm hoping this be true. In my original Hori, my jab Sanwa button lost some of it's responsiveness playing Street Fighter IV so I often lose to tech throws so hopefully this will be durable for Street Fighter V as they claim. Also, these buttons are also completely silent. I could be playing at night and nothing at all could be heard unless I of course hit the buttons hard, but that's the sound of my hand hitting any object. This is perfect for couples if a person is trying to sleep while the other person uses headphones.

I was thinking about being a pad player in the PS4 generation, but this completely changes my position of even testing that theory. I'm happy with my purchase and hope Hori continue to stay a quality company.

column6: Wolfenstein The Old Blood
column14:
If you played Wolfenstien: The New Order, you pretty much know what to expect. However, for those unfamiliar with it, playing TNO isn't mandatory since it's a prequel.

The game is a FPS, that takes place during WWII along an alternate timeline, where the Nazis have perfected robotics, cybernetics and weapon-tech. Meaning you will find yourself battling robotic super soldiers, cyborgs and well equipped soldiers eager to tear your head off.

While the game is a FPS, it does have many stealth elements. Sure, you can run in guns blazing and possibly survive. However the safer, and in my opinion way more fulfilling route, is stealthing your way through certain locations. Why blast a heavily armored super soldier when you can sneak through some air ducts and get behind him to shut off his power? Why run through a kennel and battle cyborg dogs when you can sneak up to them while they sleep and silence them quickly?

No matter which route you go, if you are a fan of W:TNO, or FPS games in general you will probably love this game. It's not without it's faults though which I will list below, but first allow me to tell you what it does well.

-Pros-
Incredibly long for a 20 dollar game
Breathtaking graphics
Excellent voice acting
Fantastic Storyline
Vent Crawling!
Good variety of enemies
Challenging gameplay with adjustable difficulty levels

-Cons-
No Multi-player
Inadequate Tutorial
Not much replay value.
Occasionally the AI can be a bit dimwitted
No manual save

column6: LEGO Batman 3: Beyond Gotham
column14:
I've noticed that other LEGO video games released for the PlayStation Vita have been getting bad reviews for poor graphics, poor gaming experience, etc. They get so much bad rep that I avoid most of these games completely, because reviews for other games of this type are trustworthy, to an extent. But when I viewed LEGO Batman 3: Beyond Gotham, I saw nothing but 4 or 5 star reviews, compared to the 1 to 3 star reviews for most others. I went with my gut and I'm glad I did.

In terms of graphics, it is mostly moderate, with the HD mostly taking up the cutscenes (of which you get most of the humor), but in terms of gameplay, it couldn't be better for a game like this. You mostly experience what you would get in a console version (I don't have the console version because I don't have a console as of yet for this game), and this time, the characters talk in-game at times, of which the rest of the humor is placed in.

As with all LEGO games, there is a lot of replay value, but the Trophy System in the Vita gives it even more replay value. I'm already almost at 50% in collecting all the trophies, with many more calling my name. And, we finally see Batman and the Justice League In SPACE.

All in all, a great alternative to most of the other LEGO games, because the graphics are better, the gameplay is better, and the humor is just as good as the console versions as other games. 5/5.

column6: Sims 4
column14:
I waited a year after purchasing this game in order to give the developers and EA time to work with the game and see what they could improve upon, but here we are almost a year after I brought the game and still not much improvement. The base game is enjoyable for a bit, but that fades quickly if you've ever played the sims 3 or the sims 2. Given the long list of game limitations such as: lack of an open world (only one lot and a small neighborhood common area loaded a time), restriction of babies to mere objects attached to cribs, lack of a toddler life stage, sims teleporting to different lots instead of actually walking/driving to the edge of the screen, lack of traditional careers, focus on cartoon cupcake makers and telescopes instead of real telescopes like in previous games, and lack of terrain editing tools, this game just breaks the level of immersion that the previous titles had for players. Every time you get caught into the game play, it's broken by either a loading screen, or a cartoon depiction of something that should have been lifelike.

Now, the game isn't without it's improvements. The multitasking system is awesome and allows for sims to take better advantage of their time, the new CAS and sims graphics allows you to create more life-like sims once you get the hang of it, and the new build/buy mode also shows some improvements in easier house making. But overall, for long-time players of The Sims series, this game will likely come as a disappointment to you. I have reverting back to playing the Sims 3 now.

EA has released several updates and patches over the past year to add things like pools (but the diving board is still MIA), and stuff packs, game packs, and expansion packs, but none have significantly changed the underlying problems with this game. I believe a better title for this release would be The Sims 1.5. It is a game that could have been built 10 years ago, and probably runs fine on computers made 10 years ago. In conclusion, I recommend waiting to see if they can fix some of the issues with the game, or wait it out until The Sims 5 (if that even happens)...don't waste your money here.conclusion, I recommend waiting to see if they can fix some of the issues with the game, or wait it out until The Sims 5 (if that even happens)...don't waste your money here.

column6: Pulse Elite Edition Wireless Stereo Headset
column13: DO NOT BUY (Cracks, Heavy, and Buzzes)
column14: I used to have this as a 5 Star.  Here are the very evident problems that far out weight any positives of the headset.  It should also be noted that I am a 14 year old using my family's account, so I don't have money to throw at $500 Turtle Beaches that last forever or a replacement.  I hoped that this would be a high quality headset that I could use on the computer, or the PS3 for a very long time (I was hoping at least 3 years).  Because I would like to remain somewhat positive (although at this point how can I?) I will start with the short list of positives.  Positives:  Microphone Sound Cancelling:  I play about 3 feet away from a speaker for the TV, as I sit in the corner.  When I ask people if they hear anything in the background, they say "No" even though I can clearly hear the sound through the headset.  This bit here is for sure a 5 Star.  Sound Options:  I can't tell huge differences in sound, so it usually doesn't affect me.  However, I must say the options are quite nice.  You can change the bass to create vibrations when an explosion or a car crash happens.  I personally didn't use this as it gave me a massive head ache when I tried it, but it is there.  You can also change the Voice Chat and Game Sound, but on the same slider.  You can also change the Game Type, from "Game" to "Racer" to "Shooter" and "Movie" however this is quite useless and I just left it on "Game" the entire time.  There is also Virtual Surround Sound (VSS) that I really liked.  I turned it off to figure out what games sounded like without VSS, and I was shocked.  This feature is great!  I cannot describe how awesome this VSS is.  The sliders and buttons on the headset are quite nice, but I could see them becoming a little broken easily.  That's it.  Nothing else is good.  Negatives  Comfort: While I did say that nothing else is good, the bit around the ear feels nice and comfortable.  The weight of the headset is crazy though, and topdoesn't help.  The top is thin, and not very thick.  This creates EXTREME discomfort.  This is one major deal breaker.  Durability: This is, again, TERRIBLE.  Let me attempt to describe where this headset CRACKED and started to creak whenever I moved at all.  The silver circles on the side of the headset I think are rumble devices for the bass.  Just below that, there is a thin "bridge" and then the shiny plate that says "Wireless Stereo Headset".  The bridge cracked on the silver side of the bridge, on both sides.  My dad got some homemade plastic that we smeared all over the bridge, and that has prevented the cracking from expanding and stopped the creaking.  This is unacceptable.  My headset should not be breaking in this manor, close enough to almost being completely broken.  Charging while playing: This issue was the straw that broke the camel's back.  The headset has terrible battery life, roughly 4-5 hours, which means charging is frequent.  Yes, you can charge and play, but recently my headset has been buzzing while being plugged in.  Pushing the end against the side of the charging port on the headset stops the buzzing, but I don't need to have homemade plastic on both sides and some tape on the headset, as the risk of taping the microphone shut is really high if I do that.  Overall, DO NOT BUY THIS HEADSET.  I know that my replacement will be Turtle Beach Stealth 400 as those are cheaper (checked before I wrote this, $78), lighter, better sound/mic quality, and overall just better than this headset.  Unfortunately for me, I need to find a $100 bill in the parking lot, or wait for Christmas.

column13: Works great, sleek design, sturdy plastic, and just looks great next to our Playstation 4!

It comes with a USB cable and hi-capacity AC adapter. The unit has two holders for controllers and expands to charge two more on the side through two ports. Our controllers fully charged in about 3 hours and I cannot tell you about four because we only have two. The included USB can be plugged into the AC adapter or into the Playstation to charge you controllers. That is great when short on plugs!
We have had our charger a few days and it has worked perfectly! It holds the controllers firmly, it does not slide around when using it, charges fast, and does all this while still looking great. You will love this charger and it is a good deal for how good the quality is. I highly recommend this for yourself or for any gamer as a gift. column6: Sniper Elite III: Collector's Edition - PlayStation 4 Collector's Edition
column13: You won't be disappointed.  Fun mechanics, good story, and wide range of levels.  Very enjoyable game.
column14:
Sniper Elite 3 was is a really fun game. It wasn't very long which was a shame but while I was playing it, I loved it.

My friend and I both purchased a copy so we play the campaign cooperatively. It was really awesome. I liked you could work together to cover each other and provide support. There was enough stealth and shooting to not disappoint. When you made a really awesome shot, the game would go into slow motion and follow the bullet which was unexpected the first time it happened but a very cool pleasant surprise.

The levels were all very different and it never felt like we were just out to go shoot people. The story is actually pretty good. There aren't a ton of different weapons to use but enough that it kept you busy and working toward that next upgrade. The mechanics of the game were really good as well. When zoomed in for a shot you can hold your breath to steady your shot, otherwise the scope would move slightly. You also have a fair amount of running and gunning. It really is up to you how you want to proceed through the level. There are definitely certain ways that the creators thought you should go through the level...killing certain people in certain places to get through without anyone noticing but more often than not, my friend and I would screw that up, get noticed and then we were in a fire fight.

Overall, I wish it was a longer game but it was cheap and free to play online with my friend. Definitely worth it because it was really fun and did not disappoint.

column14:
So there I was, so exited to smash some faces FPS style. But alas my batteries kept dying while I was in epic unyielding combat. After spending hundreds of dollars on batteries to quench my undying thirst for pixelated blood I finally decided to go out and get a play and charge kit so I could afford to eat more then just ramen warmed up with tap water while on week long tweaked out gaming sprees in my Uncles basement. But just as it seemed that my addiction for animated gore-porn would be sated my new rechargeable batteries died... But its alright, right? Because you can just recharge them? Sure you can, then they die again after an even shorter period of time. I finally just gave up and attempted to strange myself with the charging cord, but it broke so that didn't work either.

In summation, the charging part of this apparatus works just fine. The rechargeable batteries provided with it however were not genuine XBOX goodies, but some knock off brand junk that has a half-life of about a week. After being charged 4-5 times they no longer hold a charge long enough to even turn on the box.

column6: Battlefield: Bad Company 2
column14:
This has been my favorite battlefield game to date. It was also my first and I instantly fell in love with this game. I'd never even heard of the battlefield franchise before (never having been a PC gamer) and so when I tried the beta I had no idea what I was about to try. The beta was just one level repeated over and over. The weekend I played the beta, someone had lent me Cod Modern Warfare 2...and I found myself playing the beta over a full retail Cod game. It was just that good.

When the full retail game came out I played the hell out of it. The game was perfect. The gun fights were great, the vehicle combat was fantastic. There were so many epic moments when playing this game. I moved onto Battlefield 3 when it came out but I preferred Bad Company 2. I eagerly await for them to make a Bad Company 3. I don't know exactly what about Bad Company 2 made it to me so much more enjoyable than Battlefield 3. But it was.

Maybe it was the destructible environments that you never got in Battlefield 3. Or the fact that they added maps for free instead of nickle and diming you with DLC expansions and a "premium" gimmick.

Here's hoping for a Bad Company 3 soon as I passed on both Battlefield 4 and Hardline.

column6: Imagine Fashion Life - Nintendo 3DS
column14: This is an inexcusably terrible game. A classic example of cheaply made shovelware, clearly not play-tested or created with any care or thought for quality. The controls are clunky and don't work properly; the dialog reads like an unedited first draft of a bad translation from another language; and the gameplay is primarily a few extremely simplistic mini-games that have nothing to do with fashion or creativity whatsoever. The only part of the game that actually has anything to do with fashion is dressing up your avatar, however the interface is so poorly designed and the animation so laughably awful that even picking out clothes fails to be fun. The mini-games are so repetitive, simplistic and uncreative I can't imagine anyone over the age of six being entertained for more than five minutes.  Do not waste your money on this so-called "game".  If you want an actual fashion game for the 3DS, pick up Style Savvy Fashion Trendsetters. It costs more, but is worth every penny. This one was a scam at thirteen dollars.

column6: Far Cry 4
column14:
Theres tons of more in depth reviews out there, so I'll make mine short and sweet; this game is great. Only drawback for me, is I played the crap out of Far Cry 3, and unfortunately Ubisoft and their partners have done it again, which is take a formula that just works and expands on it only slightly. I've only seen one 2 new mechanics that they've added, which is the lure and the rock climbing/rope swinging. Guns are pretty much the same, some tweaks here and there for the stealth mechanics, and slightly updated graphics. Also the snowy environments are a little refreshing, and the story is just as good.

Overall, if you loved Far Cry 3, and you absolutely need to play more of it with a new story, pick this up. No regrets.

column6: Far Cry 4
column13: Play this game in co-op if you can
column14:
Far Cry 3 was fantastic. Far Cry 4 is pretty much the same as Far Cry 3. Except they added in co-op...and let me tell you. It makes a big difference when you play with a buddy. Unfortunately you can't play the main storyline campaign missions co-op. But you can do everything else (and there's a lot of it) co-op. When I first played co-op with my room mate it made me focus only on the storyline so I could leave everything else open to do in co-op. It's that fun. Yesterday we did two of the fortresses and it was a blast. I perched on a mountain overlooking the compound and provided sniper support while he went into the fortress to wreck havoc. It's too bad what you do in co-op doesn't count if you joined someone else's game. For example, if you join your friend's game and liberate a outpost that you haven't in your game, you don't get credit for it in your game. You have to do it again on your file. Even so, it's still fun.

So, Far Cry 4 is a great experience but even more so if you do it in co-op.

column6: Fallout New Vegas
column13: Let me preface this by saying I really loved playing Fallout New Vegas and this review will compare ...
column14:
Let me preface this by saying I really loved playing Fallout New Vegas and this review will compare it to Fallout 3 a lot and make some complaints. But that's because Fallout 3 was such an amazing experience that fallout the series is now held up to ridiculously high standards.

Fantastic game. However it always felt (and still does years later) like a really big DLC download that they should never have charged $ 60 for initially. The game was basically fallout 3 with a few tweaks that could have easily been implemented via patches to Fallout 3.

Aiming down the sights was great and much needed, making the gun fighting better and more FPS like. Being able to mod your guns was also a welcomed change.

The story line never felt as epic as Fallout 3's. It's ok but no where on the level of FO3.

I felt that the game could have given you more missions as a legionnaire. And speaking of factions, the game instead of focusing on karma like in FO3 focuses more on which factions you're friends with. So you could be a huge thieving, cannibalizing dirt bag with low karma but the NCR troops will be friendly towards you and say hi because you've attacked Ceaser's Legion. A silly oversight.

As for the DLC for this game, the Dead Money DLC is god awful. There's a mist that permeates large portions of the level and it automatically kills you. There's lots of other things that kill you and some holograms that are invincible. So no matter your level or skill, you'll be dying a lot the first time you go through it. I did and it was very frustrating. The worst is at the end....it's such a tease.

The other DLCS:
Honest Hearts- Not bad, no real interesting items, armor, outfits added
Old World Blues- Rather fun DLC, new interesting weapons, new perks, funny dialogue. This was probably by favorite DLC of the bunch. There's also a lot of upgrades and perks you can earn through this.
Lonesome Road- My second favorite of the DLC. Lots of new weapons and armor in this one. The story was a bit weak and a let down to me based on the build up and mystery of who the other courier was and his whole story etc.

I can't wait for Fallout 4.econd favorite of the DLC. Lots of new weapons and armor in this one. The story was a bit weak and a let down to me based on the build up and mystery of who the other courier was and his whole story etc.

I can't wait for Fallout 4.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 420X Fully Wireless Gaming Headset (Certified Refurbished) - Xbox One
column13: This headset is a step in the right direction..
column14:
After some disappointing purchases of Turtle Beaches in the past, I decided to try one more time for the perfect headset for my needs. I really did not want to spend 300+ dollars, so I decided to go middle ground with this headset. I have completed my first marathon gaming session and this 420x performed like a champ. As for the fit, the headset is very lightweight and comfortable, but the earpads were slightly stiff. Let me get right to what I thought of the sound with respect to my needs. The sound is much better than my PX4's and is on par with my Kingston HyperX Cloud II's as far as clarity and overall sound field is concerned. I would not consider myself an audiophile, but I have quite a few headsets over 100+ dollars to compare with. The 420x's don't have surround sound, this is stereo sound, but it is done with great balance throughout the sound field. Also the sound was great outside of Xbox One, I am listening to Spotify on my PS4 with my 420x's while I write this. Now onto my positive and negative points.

PRO's
-Very lightweight
-Great battery
-No hissing or distortion
-Suprisingly good stereo sound (right amount of treble and bass, not overpowering).
-ability to control every aspect of chat, mute, volume, and audio presets on the headset.
-100% wireless
-four types of audio presets
-active mic monitoring
-outstanding chat clarity
-can achieve very high volume with little to no distortion
-Microsoft's play and charge usb cable will also charge this headset. That cable is about 8 feet long.
-can work with PS4 for audio with a 3.5mm to 3.5mm cable (not included). Chat also works, I chatted in a private party on my PS4.

Secondly, now for the things I thought could be better or could be improved upon. I was concerned with the all plastic headband and frame. After asking many of the vine reviewers here on Amazon, none really answered the question of stability and if the headband was cheaply made. I reached out to Turtle Beach support and was reassured that the mistakes made with the Stealth 400 headset and the cracking headband for PS4 were not present in the 420x. I also felt that 158 dollars shipped isn't quite a great deal either, I feel that this is slightly a overpriced headset at this time.

CON's
-build quality could be much better, far to much plastic
-not a versatile headset, I will discuss this in more detail below
-149.99 is much higher than Sony's offering of the Gold Wireless Headset (wireless and simulated 7.1 surround sound) that is usually less than 99 dollars.
-not full noise cancellation
-mic monitoring is non-adjustable
-usb cable provided for charging is very short
-the overall headset headband is not flexible at all

My list of cons is mostly things that are slightly nitpicking, but this headset is really terrific overall, I am surprised at how it performs. Also this headset did work with my PS4 as well, but could not be powered by the 3.5mm alone, it needs to be plugged into the DS4 and also needs to be powered on which is going to drain the battery, this headset was made primarily for Xbox One only. It also works well with mobile devices, but this isn't a headset I would pickup for PS4, so please take my advice and go with another solution for that. My big worry is the plastic headband, I will update this in a few months to discuss durability. Despite any cons I could find, I am still going with 5 stars because this headset does many things right and not many things wrong. I commend Turtle Beach for going in the right direction with the 420x.
Update:09/27
The durability seems to be good so far, nothing is showing cracks. I have replaced the stiff earpads with Brainwavz HM5 memory foam earpads and the comfort is really great now.was cheaply made. column13: We get the point, its made in Australia!!!!!
column14: This game should have been titled Borderlands: We get it the Moon is Australia!!!  2k Australia took an established franchise with a devoted following and decided to make the story horrible, remove anything humorous from it, and add "upgrades" that you can play the entire game without using and still be okay.  First off, the lack of humor.  Borderlands 2 was very funny.  This game, well, if I hear one more reference to a term they only use in Australia as far as slang I am going to murder myself.  Second, the "upgrades" aka butt slams and laser weapons, butt slams are almost entirely useless and laser weapons are fun but too little to save this pathetic title.  Character development is terrible.  All of the new character they introduced were awful particularly the character Pickle.  2k Australia said to themselves "Hey Tiny Tina is popular lets make a character like her and people will love it".  They then proceeded to make a character that was not funny at all and that frankly I wanted to shoot in the face every time I had to deal with him.  Note to 2k Australia, if a joke is only funny on your continent then now one else will laugh.  I have never once thought to despise an entire continent for ruining something I like but thank you Australia, I can proudly say your continent sucks

column6: 8bitdo NES30 Pro Wireless Bluetooth Controller Dual Classic Joystick For iOS, Android Gamepad - PC Mac Linux
column13: The cream of a small crop
column14:
Couple this bad boy with a good laptop or tablet, and you literally have almost every game ever made at your fingertips anytime, anywhere. That's something I could only dream about when I was a kid. For the life of me, I do not understand why there are so few products on the market that fill this niche. Most of the PC controllers on Amazon have been around for almost a decade. This controller really is a breath of fresh air.

The Good: Build quality - Everything from the packaging to the finish to the button feel is in line with what you get from Sony or Nintendo OEM products. Companies that make cheap junk simply do not invest the resources that it takes to get those things right.
Style - The edge lighting is a really cool touch, and you can't beat the retro NES look.
Travel friendly - It's thin and light, yet has the full button array of a console gamepad. It easily slips into a laptop bag or backpack, and the battery life is solid.
Wireless - I hate using wired controllers, and I'm not fond of using USB dongles either. This pairs with the Bluetooth that is already in your device.

The Bad: The left analog stick does not snap back to center as it should.
There’s a learning curve to get the feel for the placement of the R1/R2 and L1/L2 buttons.

The Ugly: Getting the Bluetooth to pair takes some trial and error. On more than 1 occasion, my controller had a catastrophic crash that left it unresponsive for hours. The manufacturer has been releasing frequent firmware updates since launching this model. Maybe they will eventually get these issues ironed out, but for now, I’m definitely deducting a star from my rating.

column13: Great headset for a good price!
column14:
This headset is both useable on the PS4 and Xbone as stated above in the description. Now that is out of the way on to the review.

Sound Quality - 9/10
-Great Bass and Perfect crisp sound all around. Have used Turtle beaches and afterglow headsets and these things blow them away.

Build Quality - 7/10
-Ear cups are comfy on the head but the frame of the headset is a little cheap feeling but sturdy none the less. Good and comfy for extended use for long gaming sessions and the mic is detachable so it is not in the way when not being used.

Mic Quality - 8/10
-Good quality microphone that picks up noise very easy and sometimes a little to easy so make sure you watch your game volume when in use. Great that this thing is detachable so that when not in use it is out of the way. The background noise cancel is done very nicely and works awesome.

Anymore questions about these just leave a comment and I will try my best to answer them for you.

column6: EA SPORTS PGA TOUR
column13: Please dont waste your money like i did
column14: Probably one of the worst purchases I have ever made.  The game was fun for about 10 minutes until I realized I could hit a hole in one on every single hole or an albatross or eagle on every single par 5 or par 4 by just adusting the aim line into the hole.  Then, after playing it for 3 days, I decided to start playing online, and to make it more challenging, I turned the aim line off.  Well, when I did that, the game locked up.  Now it freezes every single time I go into the settings to try to change it back.  I contacted EA Sports about this.  Their solution was to delete everything off my xbox, gamertag, game, everything, and then reboot my internet.  So, In order to get their crappy game to work, I have to lose everything else on my xbox.  I just wrote this off as a $60 loss.  It really is a shame, because I've played the Tiger Woods franchise since it came out.  This is by far the worst effort I have ever seen.  I think the free game I got for ordering a whopper at Burger King where you got to drive the Burger King guy around was more entertaining than this.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column13: In hindsight I would not have bought.
column14:
As a big fan of the series I found this game to offer a poor experience. The graphics felt tired and aged. The gameplay was stripped to the basics and found myself pressing the same 2 buttons constantly in every enemy encounter. I also felt disconnected from the world while walking around and having someones awful taste in music getting picked up from their mics and playing through my speakers.

The game made me feel like a cookie cutter character rather than a unique entity in a world of bland missions that was too similar to World of Warcraft. I also disliked the new leveling system which made it evident I would have to rely on others for a particular specialty rather than being a jack of all trades like in Skyrim.

If I wanted a WoW game then I would have bought a WoW game. I bought Elder Scrolls because I wanted Elder Scrolls.

I happened to have purchased neither. It wasn't WoW and it wasn't Elder Scrolls. This is a game with no identity. It's no wonder they made it free to play (excluding game price), because even at free I found no pleasure in this tasteless title that is Elder Scrolls Online.

In hindsight I would not have bought this game.

column6: Final Fantasy Type - 0 HD
column13: An ok game to get from the bargain bin, not worth the $40 I paid - I wouldn't even pay $20 on this one.
column14:
Game forces you to be fast paced in battles, and wants you to play through it more than once. On EASY mode, my first playthrough, I was consistently running into enemies that were pretty high level, and often had quests that demanded my characters be high level - most recommended a second playthrough before attempting these optional battles. To me these comprised of about half of the game, as I only did the bare minimum to get Platinum trophy. Got bored grinding, which I did a couple of times, as the enemies didn't seem too vastly different.

Can't freely explore as you need to unlock regions based on the chapter you're at. Worst of all is the game's story was really dry, and except for missions, none of the additional tasks/NPC talks really added anything to the story or enjoyment of the game. Pretty boring overall. Buy it when it's in the bargain bin.

column6: Polk Audio N1 Bar
column14:
Love the headset, sound comes in clear and headset is comfortable to wear. The headset feels well built and is not to heavy in my opinion.
I did purchase this for my Xbox one and you do have to contact the company to get the controller puck and boom mic attachment. I have used it on my Xbox 360 for audio and chat and it worked great.
If you do plan on using it for the Xbox one, you need the puck if you have the old controller and you need the boom mic or you will not have good chat function.
I own the Turtle Beach X12's for about 4 years and the sound to me on the Polk comes in cleaner. Over all I liked my Turtle Beach X12's, but they are not compatible with the Xbox one unless I want to use my kinect, and I really don't want that.
I have worn the headset for over 3 hours and did not receive a headache from the head band squeezing to hard. My ears did sweat a little, but I come to expect that and that might be me. I did have head set cut out, but so did my controller. So I think that might be a Xbox one issue.
Overall I am pleased with the the headset and Polk customer service was easy to deal with.

column6: Xim 4 Keyboard and Mouse Adapter for PS4, Xbox One, 360, PS3
column14:
I'm normally a pc player because I enjoy playing shooters with mouse and keyboard. The level of skill I get to in a game is usually averaging 2/1 or 3/1 kill to death.

The good is that this tracks good enough you may forget this isn't on a pc. I used this on ps4 destiny and first did a search to find someone else's settings because it was a little off with the default. This guy's settings work great. I'm finding that a combination of what appears to be lag (even though my connection doesnt lag on pc) and builtin auto aim can be a little akward when they interact, and i only know this because I'm now very precise with aiming. Regardless of this, if you like facts i went from around .33 k/d matches to averaging around 1. Still learning maps and the gear to do better.

The gui you use on your phone with bluetooth connection simple enough and intuitive to use. You can also do a lot of interesting things if you are inclined... setting up x/y sensativity to turn faster but still have precise slower moves.

The only frustrating thing is the detection of devices and if you let it sit for awhile and watch a movie on your ps4. It might have lost connection to everything leaving you plugging and unplugging things. Same happens when entering a game you may have to unplug and replug cables. Maybe I just don't know the secrets, would be nice if their were no initialization issues.

Either way, mouse and keyboard on the ps4 is now a real thing that has been done well.

column6: Middle Earth: Shadow of Mordor
column13: a pun) and took everyone by surprise with how great it was
column14:
Game came out of the shadows (hey look, a pun) and took everyone by surprise with how great it was. Before this game I can't think of one great Lord of the Rings video game. So when this game came out and all of a sudden people were giving it glowing reviews I was intrigued. And I did something I rarely do. I bought a video game I didn't know anything about.

And I had a great time with it.

So let's complain first shall we? Negatives:
The main character is utterly forgettable. It's weird. Everyone else in the game is modeled so well and look like they fit the Lord of the Rings universe. But the main character (whose name I can't even remember) is forgettable and really just looks like a cheap imitation of Aragorn. He looks like how the main character of a game that was bastardizing The Lord of The Rings would look like.
It's easy to get overwhelemed with how much there is to do in the game. I found myself just going after captains every time I sat down to play. And then I forgot what I was even doing in the main quest line and I stopped playing for a while.
The story is very weak.
The end boss/last level was a let down.

Positives:
Combat is terrific. If you're going to rip off others, rip off the best. And they did so by ripping off Batman and Assassins Creed. So the combat is great. The voice acting is good.
It's got a lot to do (although might be too much as I said in the negatives)
Great graphics.
Nemesis system was very unique and well thought out.

It'll be interesting to see what they do with the inevitable sequel.

column6: Watch Dogs
column14: When Watch Dogs arrived in May 2014, it had a tumultuous reception. There was a big uproar about how the hype was false, how the videos shown at E3 didn't reflect the final state of the game, and that customers were lied to. Then there were complaints of technical issues with the game (which were supposedly patched later). Then there were complaints that the game just wasn't very good. Some liked the game, but for others, the game left a poor taste in their mouths, whether affected by the hype or not, it was unclear.  I was interested enough that I kept the game on my radar, but I was in no hurry to check it out. Over a year later I picked it up for the price of $10. I went into it with a fairly open mind, knowing it wasn't going to be a great game, but also expecting that many had reviled it based on broken expectations and the negativity hype. Unfortunately, I didn't find a sleeper hit or an unappreciated game. Yet it wasn't completely terrible game either. I want to share thoughts on Watch Dogs over some of the better games I've played just because it's interesting how it has so much potential to be better and just keeps missing the target.  The first thing you notice when you play is that it's more like Grand Theft Auto than you expected. We all knew it was open world in a modern city from videos, but coming from Ubisoft, the makers of open world Assassin's Creed games, I didn't expect it to be so much like GTA. I, like others, expected more like Assassin's Creed in the modern day, some climbing, infiltration, etc. No, you can't climb more than in a few spots. Getting around and doing stuff is just like GTA, except a little worse. Driving is not nearly as polished as you want. Shooting is fine for the most part. The city of Chicago looks great, but it feels empty. It has as many people as most GTA games, but for the actual city of Chicago, it's a ghost town. The biggest thing the game lacks compared to a comparable GTA or Saints Row is that Watch Dog lacks the fun and personality they have, but I'll get to that in a bit.  Gameplay-wise, the whole point of playing Watch Dogs is the hacking mechanic. Using the protagonist's phone, you can tap into the citywide ctOS system that has been installed in this fictional Chicago. This allows you to see information on any person around you, steal from their bank accounts, disable alarms, and hack systems. You can tap into any camera and then scan people or find other hacking opportunities. For whatever fictional reasoning, this requires line of sight, so often you need to hack a camera, from that camera look around so you have line of sight to hack another camera, and so on until you find the thing you want to hack. This often happens with security doors, where you'll get a highlighted path for the circuit and need to track it back to the switch. Once you get upgrades, hacking also allows you to raise and lower bridges, explode steam pipes under cars, raise road spikes, and other things to help you in car chases. Hacking also allows an alternative in most violent situations. Many times in the game you'll need to enter a secure area where enemies attack you on sight. Often you can hack cameras before stepping into the area. This allows you to scout the area... and cause mayhem. You can change the environment and distract the guards, but with the right upgrades, you can kill too. Watching through the cameras, you can hack circuits to explode and kill guards near them, you can set off grenades in guards' pockets, and more. Often you can soften up the guards or even kill them all through hacking. In some cases you can achieve your objective without ever stepping into the restricted area. Depending on how you do it, it can take longer than a frontal assault, but it sure is fun. When it is working, hacking is a fun part of Watch Dogs.  Which is disappointing, because that fun hacking mechanic is the top shelf feature in a game that really isn't very fun. With an interesting mechanic and apassable GTA-style open world, it's unfortunate that they made such a boring game. The story of Watch Dogs is a lesson in how to make the player not care. Set in present day Chicago, players take on the role of GravellyVoice McBadChoices (actually Aiden Pearce, but you're not going to remember that) as he tries to correct his past and we struggle to care. Aiden is a hacker-slash-thug who has been also moonlighting in town as The Vigilante (I think? It's more mentioned over and over in passing than really explained). Sometime before the start of the game, he did a job that went bad, and as retribution an assassin was sent after his sister's family and his niece was killed. GravellyVoice blames himself, so he's tracking them down to get revenge, even though his sister - the girl's mother - and pretty much everyone else says not to do it, it's not worth it, and they don't even want him to do it. But GravellyVoice McBadChoices ignores them and explores vengeance for all of, like, two missions before he's pulled into something nobody gives a damn about (not even GravellyVoice!) and his family is in danger. In a world where only gravelly-voiced protagonists can do anything, he must do what he can to save them, which means going on missions because he was told to. At least in GTA and Saints Row we get colorful characters that are amusing when telling us to do bitch work, sometimes even parodying it, but Watch Dog plays it completely serious even when ridiculous and uninspired. Eventually it makes its way back around to the vengeance angle and dips its hands into some interesting topics, but revenge takes a back seat for a long time to make you do other stuff first.  When I saw videos and marketing for Watch Dogs, I thought it would be a darker crime thriller focusing on privacy issues, corporate overreach, and information age issues. Those issues are sort of in the game, more in the late game, but for a good chunk of the game, those are setup for another plot. Instead of the cyberage concerns, I found myself dealing with low income area gangsters, sex trafficking, and occasionally stopping petty crimes for no reason. Yes, you have the option of stopping petty crimes you are alerted to on the map, but there's few explanations why you, the player, or why the character, GravellyVoice McBadChoices, would want to do them. In fact, you can "mess them up" by making the criminal run away, but the game counts this as a failure, only rewarding you for waiting until the criminal does the crime (sometimes killing the victim) and then taking them down. I would think chasing off the criminal would be a win too. Overall, these petty crimes are rarely fun. There's a meter for how good or bad a reputation GravellyVoice has, and stopping crime raises it (and running over pedestrians decreases it), but other than telling me it exists, the game never really explained what it did, and it never had any effect on my game experience.  Watch Dogs is full of side content and systems, but many of them are either poorly explained or of no consequence. In that respect, it feels much like Assassin's Creed 3, also by Ubisoft: it feels like a bunch of development teams worked on this, each doing a different system and content line, so there's a bunch of stuff in the game, but none of it feels very deep. There are half a dozen different collectibles, maybe half a dozen investigations (which are like collectibles but slightly different), ctOS towers to unlock (like Assassin's Creed viewpoints but more hacking, less climbing), lots of violence related side missions (gang headquarters, fixer assignments, driving activities), two VR games (shooting, and 8-bit style gold collection), city activities (poker, drinking games, etc) and four side game activities called Digital Trips with their own areas, rules, and skill trees (which are actually more fun than the main game). If you're a person who only buys a game every few months and plays the crap out of it, then this game has much to occupy you. Likewise if you're a completionist that must do everything, there's a ton to do. But like I said, it's not all fun. The game does reward you well for completing side content - you unlock guns, cars, and outfits. I appreciate that, except for the fact that most guns, cars, and outfits are not useful. The game lacks versatility in its assets, so once you've unlocked the best of something, you don't need the others. I never needed thirty guns across five equipped categories - I needed two guns, a silenced pistol and an assault rifle, which even reduced to one when they inexplicably gave me a silenced assault rifle (which is magic, by the way). I used a sniper rifle maybe three times and a grenade launcher for a single difficult hallway battle, but both of those times the assault rifle would have worked well too.  The game is not without its control and design issues. I really disliked weapon switching. In Watch Dogs, you don't pick which guns you carry with you, you have them all with you. You hold left bumper to bring up the weapon wheel, which has one of every gun type (pistol, assault rifle, shotgun, etc). If you want to select a different assault rifle, you hold left bumper, use right thumbstick to highlight the gun (which felt oversensitive, as half the time when you let go of the thumbstick it switched to something else) and then you use the D-pad to cycle through guns. This was a frustrating set of hand movements for me. The game doesn't pause when you do this either, so changing a gun in a firefight can be frustrating. Also, cycling through/switching your equipped gun automatically takes it out. And unlike some other games, pedestrians immediately react. So if you're at a weapon shop and want to equip some of the guns you just bought, you cycle through the weapons and equip the weapon. The customers and weapon store owner freak out like you're robbing the place. Cops are called and you can't buy anymore guns... just because I equipped the gun he just sold me.  It can be frustrating due to difficult design or just inconsistencies. With ctOS, you can track people across town, hack their phones from afar, etc. But you still have a mission where you need to tail someone via car and not be seen, even though you already have hacked their phone - why is the GPS suddenly not working? Then he gets out of the car and you need to follow him on foot, but now the distance you have to keep is suddenly much smaller than the car. Watch Dogs also has more than a few instafail stealth mission - getting seen means the mission immediately ends, no chance to kill the dude before he tells someone, no chance to fight your way through. Just over immediately, restart. It also has one of the most frustrating boss fights I have experienced in recent memory. They put you in a cramped area with various pieces of cover. Once you enter the area you are given no new objective. The villain monologues a minute or so, you get attacked by three dudes. Kill them, and the villain monologues another minute or two. Then one of the biggest elites of the game just appears in this cramped area and you need to kill him and someone else in the scant seconds before you are ripped to shreds. Needless to say you will die the first time. You restart and guess what? You have to listen to the same villain monologues without a word changed. And the action won't start until he finishes, and you can't skip the dialog. The fight is still frustratingly hard, so you might hear this monologue eight, nine, more times. And it wasn't even a very good monologue the first time.  The car radios in the game have a selection of tracks you can listen to as you drive. You can steal them from certain pedestrians' phones. The tracks would be nice, except I've rarely listened to more than the first minute and a half of a song. You have hideouts you can fast travel to which keep you from long trips. When you're on a story mission which is the only time you can't use fast travel, the game plays its own mood music, keeping the track/radio music muted. When you are in a car and wanting to listen to music, it still gets interrupted by alerts of new missions, news broadcasts, or random story phone calls. After you finish each story mission, there are some very lengthy phone calls. Usually only one or two and right after another. But occasionally they have more once you get closer to the next story mission icon. I remember getting in my car, switching through twenty tracks, putting on a favorite Weezer song I was glad to see in the game, driving toward a side mission to waste time with, and then having this bitch call me on the phone and then talk through the whole damn song. Add to this the fact that music stops when you get out of the car, and you never really get to enjoy the music. Why was it put in? Probably because it was on a checklist rather than it made sense. There's a lot more design issues/bugs like this, but I think you get the picture.  At this point, you might be wondering why I spent the time to write this up or why I'm kicking a dead franchise horse. It comes down to seeing what they did right in this game that makes me want to see something else. I'm actually curious to see a Watch Dogs 2. Let's draw a parallel between Watch Dogs and Assassin's Creed - not completely unreasonable, since they are both by the same publisher, but I have no idea if the same dev team. Assassin's Creed 1 was full of promise and good ideas, but its execution left us with a game with some good mechanics but lots of boring gameplay and story. From that meager, almost tech demoish game came Assassin's Creed 2, a sequel that far exceeded its predecessor, taking the original game and making it into a well-done, polished game that corrected nearly every flaw of the first. Watch Dogs 2 could be that. Rather than being a first stab in the dark at something new, Watch Dogs 2 could be built on this foundation, correcting design issues and retuning to a better direction for the franchise.  Of course, I think the biggest missed opportunity of this game is plot and setting. As a present day game, Watch Dogs just doesn't work. Its blend of the familiar and unfamiliar comes off in a bad way, jarring and uninteresting. But look at the mechanics it has to work with - this would make a great CYBERPUNK game. Set it 100 years in the future, in a setting along the lines of Deus Ex or Shadowrun. All of its best parts - hacking, a gun system, crime, a big city - would fit perfectly. Instead of Watch Dogs' plot, put Blade Runner, Judge Dredd, and PsychoPass into a blender, then attach that output to Watch Dogs' hacking, shooting, and open world mechanics. That is the game I want to play. It was the specter that haunted me through my entire Watch Dogs experience.  Ultimately, Watch Dogs is a hard game to recommend if you just want to play a good game I wouldn't spend more than $10-15 on it, no matter what reason you have. If you want one game you can do stuff with over weeks/months, it's not a bad game. If you want to check out a fun hacking mechanic as a player, a game archeologist, or a game developer, then it's worth you to give the game a try. But I can't recommend it just for the game itself. Once you walk away from the game, you're never going to remember the story of GravellyVoice McBadChoices, and if you are, it's going to be for his nonsensical choices or his confusing sociopathic epilogue monologue. If you're just looking for a game to play for solid story and gameplay, you should find something else.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column14:
OK, I'll be brutally honest. This version has killed the Elder Scrolls franchise for me. I've had thousands of hours of enjoyment with Morrowind, Oblivion, and Skyrim, and generally always have a Oblivion and Skyrim game running.
But this, ug. By taking it on-line and restricting what you can do unless you play more (on top of the high initial cost) I can't play it. I won't pay the subscription price (Hey, I paid more than $60) all one can do is a silly bunch of fetch and carry missions.
Also, forget the traditional open world. Your exploration is very limited. You're stuck in small regions until you do meaningless tasks. And, as I mentioned, you can't do dungeons unless you pay more.
The leveling system is obscure.
My gut tells me they looked at Neverwinter on-line and dumbed that down.
I've played 15 hours worth, and won't launch it again. In fact, I've started a new Skyrim campaign to get this thing out of my head.
Next installation Bethesda, go back to your roots and let us single-players have a rich open world where we can do the entire range of things.

column6: Mass Effect 2
column13: I bought a PS3 near launch and didn't want to buy another system but Mass Effect seemed that awesome. When they announced it was
column14:
The Mass Effect trilogy was going to be the reason I bought an Xbox 360. I bought a PS3 near launch and didn't want to buy another system but Mass Effect seemed that awesome. When they announced it was coming to the Playstation I rejoiced. It's a fantastic game. Bioware created a great trilogy and the mass effect world is so immersive you can lose chunks of time just reading all the codex entries. If you have any fascination with astronomy, it's very cool to see them visit different parts of the milky way you're familiar with. The gameplay is fun, storyline is epic, characters are really memorable and easy to care about and relate to and the voice acting is TOP NOTCH. Voices fit their characters so well, whereas other games will have such terrible voice acting it pulls you out of the experience (looking at you Heavy Rain and Destiny) the voice acting here will further immerse you. Kudos to who ever makes the voice casting decisions and the voice recording director.

If you haven't played the mass effect trilogy, do so. It's phenomenal.

column6: Wii Fit Game with Balance Board
column14:
I've been using this now for a few months. It makes working out fun and I feel like even though it's not what most people would imagine when they hear someone is working out, if it gets you moving more than you normally would be, it's worth trying. When I find time to use Wii Fit, I do a body test to measure my balance, BMI, and weight, one activity from each category twice (except aerobics, that one I change up..depending on how much time it takes I'll do anything from 2 activities once each or 3 activities twice each) and another body test to see if anything has changed. During my more work out heavy weeks, I do tend to notice a gradual loss of weight. The little pet they give you also gives some tips and explanations.

I would agree that going out and getting a full work out at a gym is more effective, but that's if you're motivated enough on your own to actually go do that every couple of days. It's also more expensive to and there's hardly any parking around here and when there is, you have to pay for it. I expect to work my way up to that, but for now, this is a great solution imo!

column6: Heavy Rain - Greatest Hits
column13: It's a good game and should be played and enjoyed
column14:
Game had a lot of potential. It's a good game and should be played and enjoyed. But there's some stuff holding it back from being the classic it could have been.

Clunky controls, bad voice acting, and plot holes (there's one gaping plot hole that I won't say as it gives away a twist in the game).

The controls don't have to be as refined as say Grand Theft Auto for a game to be enjoyable, and the TellTale games are a testament to that. Speaking of TellTale games are what Heavy Rain wishes it could be. Play through The Walking Dead or their Game of Thrones games and you see that the controls are not ever meant to be the highlight of the game. It's the story, characters, plot developments and voice acting that is at center stage.

Heavy Rain has some bad voice acting that really pulls you out of the game at times ....(let's not forget JAAAAAAAAASON).

The story line was decent and did have me compelled the first time through...till you realize all the plot holes at the end. If you never played the game you should give it a go.

column6: Thrustmaster TX Racing Wheel Ferrari 458 Italia Edition
column13: Fantastic Racing Wheel That's Worth the Money
column14: I give this 4 1/2 stars. I was lucky enough to get one that was working perfectly, even after weeks of settings on my games at 100% force feedback. It also came with the latest firmware already installed. The force feedback is really strong and you can always tell when you're losing traction. There's a bit of a learning curve, if you buy this for Forza 5, I recommend starting with 360 degrees and slowly working your way up to 900. If you start with maximum settings and no experience, it'll be very hard to control. I took off a half point because of the stock wheel. If you're not picky, it has rubber grips where your hands are and metal paddles. If you are a seasoned professional sim addict, however, I recommend the full rubber GTE rim or, for $50 more, the full leather and brushed steel rim offered by Thrustmaster. The brake and gas paddles are fine, they do the job and are made of metal. I also recommend purchasing a Wheelstand Pro with this. It will give you incredible stability and the comfort of being able to put it away when not in use. Either way, the desk clamp is also efficient and does it's job very well. Overall, with some upgrade parts from Thrustmaster or just by itself, this is the best wheel for Xbox One and I highly recommend it.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column14:
For the first 10 or so levels of this game, I hated it. I had already looked up the trade in value at Best Buy and made the decision to trade it in. After watching a few YouTube videos of the gameplay, I decided to give it another shot. As I increased my level, started to pay attention to the lore/guild quests and became more accustomed to the travel system, I found a lot to like about the game. That being said, there are a lot of issues that need to be worked out before I can count ESO among the great online MMO's. I've detailed a few pros and cons below. I gave the game 4 stars, but I would rate it 3.5 if it would let me.

PRO'S
1.) It is different. There are a lot of people that are saying how different this is than Skyrim. While the story isn't nearly as tight as Skyrim, you would be a little daft not to see the similarities. The combat and feel of the game are pure Elder Scrolls. The combat, love it or hate it, is one of a kind in MMO's. While I personally believe that the no lock on, free flow combat style of the Elder Scrolls series worked fine for the single player games, a lock on system would be very beneficial for the MMO aspect. I really wouldn't hold my breath for that though, since that would probably take a whole combat design rewrite.

2.) Free to play. I have never really been tempted to buy anything from the crown store at all. I did buy a horse, but it was only because I didn't want to wait to start leveling it up. All the stuff you can buy is completely optional (at least until the DLC gets released).

3.) First person mode. I am in the minority here, but I absolutely love playing in first person. People tell me about how much of a disadvantage that puts me in during combat, but I do not care. This is one of the only MMO's that lets me play in first person mode. I personally hate the third person perspective (it makes me a little queasy for some reason).

4.) The main story quests. The main story quests along with the guild quests are very well done. The quests are fully voiced and pretty fun to run through. You can tell there was a lot of effort put into making the quests as meaningful as you can in an MMO.

CON'S

1.) GROUPING. This is the glaring problem I have with ESO at this point. The dungeon finder doesn't function as well as it should and even when it does, there can be long waits for groups. This causes people to be either in the middle of other quests or AFK by the time you finally get a group (and I play a tank). Also, since most people do the "any dungeon" option, the game doesn't give you the option to fast travel to a specific dungeon. You literally just appear in a four man group and are supposed to get to whatever dungeon you want the group to do. In a nutshell, this means 30+ minutes to find the group, 15+ minutes of people talking about which dungeon to do, plus 15-20 minutes waiting on that 4th guy that isn't on the same page as everyone else to get to the dungeon. You can fast travel to anyone else in the group, which is nice, but unless the whole group is ATK and ready you are still screwed. There needs to either be a quick voting option for dungeons once the group is formed or just let the game pick for you (if you picked random). Then the whole group can get the option to respond and be transported to the entrance to the dungeon (Like WoW). The whole grouping thing is often made worse by the second CON on my list.....

2.) Communication. The chat is local/group/guild VOICE only. When this works it is amazing. When you have a good 4 man group of guys (or gals) chatting your way through a dungeon it is an awesome experience. When everyone has a mic and at least an average level of intelligence, ESO has some of the best grouping in any MMO I've played. Unfortunately, oftentimes this isn't the case. Some people refuse to get a mic or even put their volume up so they can hear the rest of the group. This causes a lot of issues because there is no other way to communicate. Many groups have wiped over and over again due to a lack of any way to communicate with certain members. People have been asking for text chat, but I am not sure that would work much better in a console setting. Local chat is almost always useless and filled with children either playing stupid radio songs or high pitched screeching sounds. This is something that needs to be dealt with sooner rather than later.

3.) Side quests. While the main quests are well done, the side quests are pointless. For some reason, side quests give very little in the way of rewards. They are very low EXP and if there is a prize, it is usually a lot amount of gold or a crappy item. There are no faction lines or any other reasons at all to complete these quests. It is infinitely quicker to level up by just killing random enemies over and over than by doing the side quests. There needs to be some incentive to do these side quests as there are a huge amount of them in the game.

While this wasn't a definitive list, it is my main thoughts on the state of the game. The game is still very new on consoles, so I hope some of the issues can be ironed out over the coming months. If ESO can fix some of its grouping/communication issues and add better end game content it can absolutely be in it for the long haul. If you liked Skyrim or just the ES series in general then this game is worth a try.f the group. This causes a lot of issues because there is no other way to communicate. Many groups have wiped over and over again due to a lack of any way to communicate with certain members. People have been asking for text chat, but I am not sure that would work much better in a console setting. Local chat is almost always useless and filled with children either playing stupid radio songs or high pitched screeching sounds. This is something that needs to be dealt with sooner rather than later.

3.) Side quests. While the main quests are well done, the side quests are pointless. For some reason, side quests give very little in the way of rewards. They are very low EXP and if there is a prize, it is usually a lot amount of gold or a crappy item. There are no faction lines or any other reasons at all to complete these quests. It is infinitely quicker to level up by just killing random enemies over and over than by doing the side quests. There needs to be some incentive to do these side quests as there are a huge amount of them in the game.

While this wasn't a definitive list, it is my main thoughts on the state of the game. The game is still very new on consoles, so I hope some of the issues can be ironed out over the coming months. If ESO can fix some of its grouping/communication issues and add better end game content it can absolutely be in it for the long haul. If you liked Skyrim or just the ES series in general then this game is worth a try.

column6: Kirby & The Rainbow Curse
column13: This game is greatly compromised by the lack of refinement in the controls.
column14: In my opinion, this game has beautiful, clay-like graphics, and nice, classy music. I like how cute and colorful the game is... However, it seems to me that the game's development was somewhat rushed. The most glaring example of this is that the stylus controls are not well done. I think it's fun and fresh to control Kirby in a creative way by drawing lines with a stylus on the tablet, but in my opinion Nintendo has done a poor implementation of these controls. It seems to me that Kirby often does not get onto a line drawn, even if it is started on top of him, or directly below him (where I'd imagine his paws are). Also, I noticed that lines often erase so quickly by the game that it seems to compromise the gameplay, and multiple interconnecting lines have to be used - all while hoping that the dubious controls code will work correctly at the intersection(s), which is often not the case. I would expect that Kirby would run towards the beginning of a rainbow line (at least as long as it was accessible from where he is), which he generally does not do in my experience. I think it has the potential to be a great game, but needs a well-coded controls software patch to realize more of its potential. Especially for a Nintendo game, I was very disappointed in this lack of controls refinement.

column6: Style Savvy: Trendsetters - Nintendo 3DS
column13: A standard all other fashion games should aspire to.
column14:
Wow. This game was such a surprise. So many fashion games are cheaply and poorly made, this one puts all the others to shame. It's not simply a great fashion game, it's one of the best games made for the 3DS platform in any genre.

First, and most importantly, there are over 10,000 articles of clothing for the player to acquire in the game. The clothes are arranged so that the player can experiment with practically infinite combinations to create outfits. You do not simply pick a dress, you choose a shirt, an undershirt, skirt or pants, jacket, hat, gloves, necklace, tights or socks, and shoes. There is also a lot of variety in the styles of the clothes, everything from daring and bold to sweet and conservative, to goth lolita or harajuku pop. The options are endless.

There is much more to the game play than simply dress up though. The game has the player character play the part of a store manager, helping customers with requests, learning about what styles appeal to which customers, managing the back room stocks and purchasing new styles from suppliers. You also promote your store by participating in competitive fashion shows which get more and more challenging as you play.

The store management might be too difficult for young children to play without adult help, but anyone above ten or so should get hours and hours of fun from this game.

column13: when I first got the controller I neglected to charge it the recommended 1 - 2 hours
column14: Let me start by saying this controller is very well built and when it works it does exactly what I need it to. Now, when I first got the controller I neglected to charge it the recommended 1 - 2 hours. I initially thought this caused an issue I encountered where the controller would not power on unless it was plugged in. Yes it charged, yes I'm sure, yes I held the button in for 3 or more seconds. It never came on if it was unplugged. Once I plugged it in and powered it on I could unplug it and worked like magic. I've had the controller maybe three weeks now, and I was using fine about an hour ago. I just went to plug it in to turn it on and it will no longer charge. Yes I'm sure the cable works, no I didn't drop or damage it in any way shape or form, yes I'm kinda bummed about it. Bottom line is that is two-too-many issues to have with a brand new device that is advertised as a high quality merchandise. Maybe Nyko isn't the brand for me.

column6: Ortz PS4 Vertical Stand with Cooling Fan - Controller Charging Station with Dual Charger
column13: At first I thought this was great because going vertical saved space
column14: At first I thought this was great because going vertical saved space. After a couple of days on my new ps4 it started acting strange and felt warm and cutting off randomly. So I unplugged vertical cooling stand and placed my ps4 horizontal again and back into its well ventilated space again with a normal house fan and haven't had a problem since. If you look closely at the vents you can see were being horizontal to me makes more sense as all the components can cool equally. Vertical the lower parts heat runs up through the rest of the system as we all know heat rises. I am not saying that the ps4 isn't made to run vertical  because it is, but if you play alot of hours you may want to re think this. And some of you may have used this unit with know problems. I only know that it didn't work well for me.

I went to Fry's, after getting this, and bought a Seagate 2TB External Backup Plus Slim drive. Plugged it into my Windows 10 computer and [Right-Click] Start then Disk Management. Found the drive and Deleted the volume. This brought it to an Unformatted/Unpartitioned stated.

I then promptly Ripped it apart to get the drive out of it. (For WHATEVER reason, the External 2TB's are always 25%-50% cheaper than stand alone drives.)

I opened the Drive panel on this enclosure and plugged the hard drive into it. Closed the panel. DO NOT PLUG IT IN YET!

Powered ON the Xbox. Once it was at my main screen, I plugged this into the side. Within a few seconds DO YOU WANT TO FORMAT THIS DRIVE? Heck yeah! It is, also, now selected as my Primary download drive. Anything I need intense speed from, I'll copy it back to main 500GB drive.

All in all... GET THIS IF YOU HAVE AN XBOX ONE!!!

11/17/15 update. STILL ROCKS!

02/04/16 update. STILL ROCKS!
